The two candidates give different elements of the Grothendieck–Witt ring.

• Candidate 1: ½ · (2j choose j) · (⟨1⟩ + ⟨u⟩)  
  = ( (2j choose j)/2 ) copies of ⟨1⟩ plus the same number of copies of ⟨u⟩.

• Candidate 2: (2j choose j) · ⟨1⟩  
  = (2j choose j) copies of ⟨1⟩ only.

Even though ½·(2j choose j) is an integer (since (2j choose j) is always even for j > 0), the two expressions differ in their anisotropic part (Candidate 1 includes ⟨u⟩’s, Candidate 2 does not). Hence they are not equivalent in GW(𝔽_q).

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different elements of the Grothendieck–Witt group.

• Candidate 1:  (½) · (2j choose j) · (1 + u)  
 This is ( (2j choose j)/2 ) copies of the hyperbolic plane, whose rank equals (2j choose j).

• Candidate 2:  ⟨1⟩ + ⟨−1⟩  
 This is exactly one hyperbolic plane (rank 2).

These two coincide only in the special case j = 1 (when (2j choose j)/2 = 1), but the question asks for general non-negative j. Hence, in general, the answers are not the same.

The two expressions being compared are

Candidate 1: ∫   \overline{sgn(f(x))}\,|f(x)|^{p-1}\,g(x) dλ(x)=0

Candidate 2: ∫   |f(x)|^{p-2}\,f(x)\,g(x) dμ(x)=0

Observe that
 |f|^{p-2} f = sgn(f) |f|^{p-1} (for real-valued f),
whereas for complex-valued f we have
 \overline{sgn(f)} |f|^{p-1} = \overline{f}\,|f|^{p-2}.

Thus:

• In the real case the integrands in Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 coincide, so the conditions are the same.

• In the complex case they differ by complex conjugation: Candidate 1 uses \overline{f}|f|^{p-2} g, whereas Candidate 2 uses f|f|^{p-2} g. The standard Birkhoff-orthogonality condition in the complex Lᵖ space involves the conjugate (as in Candidate 1), so the two candidates are not equivalent for complex functions.

Because the original question does not restrict to real functions and Candidate 1 explicitly includes the conjugation while Candidate 2 does not, the two candidates cannot be regarded as universally equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

Even after accounting for the common prefactor q^{maj(σ)+maj(π)}, the remaining factors are not the same: candidate 1 has a product of two q-binomials and an extra q-power, whereas candidate 2 has only one q-binomial. The question asks for two explicit cardinalities (one for \(2k+1\) and one for \(2k\)).  
Both candidates supply two formulas, so Rule 2 is satisfied.  

Compare the formulas:

1. Candidate 1 (odd):  
   \(|A_{\mathbb Z[i],2k+1}| = 14\cdot4^{k+1}-34\cdot2^{k+1}+8k+29\).  
   This grows on the order of \(4^{k}\).

   Candidate 2 (odd):  
   \(|A_{\mathbb Z[i],2k+1}| = 4\,\sum_{d\mid(2k+1)}\chi(d)\).  
   The sum over the Dirichlet character \(\chi\) is bounded by the divisor count of \(2k+1\), i.e. \(O(k^\varepsilon)\); it is at most a small integer.

   These two expressions cannot coincide for all \(k\) (the first is exponential, the second is at most polynomially bounded).  

2. Candidate 1 (even):  
   \(|A_{\mathbb Z[i],2k}| = 28\cdot4^{k}-48\cdot2^{k}+8k+25\) (also exponential).

   Candidate 2 (even):  
   \(|A_{\mathbb Z[i],2k}| = 4\,\sum_{d\mid m}\chi(d)\) where \(m\) is the odd part of \(k\).  
   Again this is bounded by a small integer independent of any power \(4^{k}\).

Since the growth behaviours are fundamentally incompatible, the two candidates give different answers for both sub-problems.

Both candidates assert that the value of \(f(x,y)\) is zero for every \(x,y\in\mathcal G\):
• Candidate 1 explicitly states “\(f(x,y)=0\).”
• Candidate 2 answers simply “0,” which, in context, likewise means \(f(x,y)=0\) for all inputs.

The responses convey the same single result, fulfilling the problem’s requirement. Therefore, they are equivalent.  

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give the same functional value:

• Candidate 1 explicitly states “f(x,y) = 0.”  
• Candidate 2 states simply “0,” which, in the context of the question “What is the value of f(x,y) for all x,y ∈ 𝔊?,” clearly implies that the value is 0 for every pair (x,y).

There is only one required answer, no unit ambiguity, and both convey the identical result.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two expressions are structurally different.

Candidate 1 (q-Pochhammer):
(-q^r; ε q^{r+t+s})_∞ = ∏_{k=0}^{∞} ( 1 − (−q^r)(ε q^{r+t+s})^k )
                    = ∏_{k=0}^{∞} ( 1 + ε^k q^{\,r + (r+t+s)k} ).

Its factors are
1 + ε^k q^{r + (r+t+s)k}         for k = 0,1,2,…

Candidate 2 (separated products):
∏_{m=1}^{∞} (1 + q^{\,r(2m−1)+t}) · ∏_{m=1}^{∞} (1 − ε q^{s m}).

The first group of factors involves exponents r(2m−1)+t (always with a “+” sign), and the second group involves exponents s m with a sign that is independent of k in the first group.

Because

• the exponents in Candidate 1 are r + k(r+t+s) (e.g. r, 2r+t+s, 3r+2t+2s,…), which do not match the two separate arithmetic progressions appearing in Candidate 2, and  
• the signs of the individual factors in Candidate 1 alternate with ε^k, whereas in Candidate 2 the signs are fixed in each of the two products,

the two infinite products cannot, in general, be the same expression. A simple numerical choice (e.g. r = 1, t = 0, s = 1, ε = 1) already shows Candidate 1 reduces to ∏_{k≥0}(1+q^{2k+1}) while Candidate 2 contains an extra factor ∏_{m≥1}(1−q^{m}).

Hence the predictions are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two answers give two different infinite-product (q-Pochhammer) expressions:

Candidate 1: (-q^r ; ε q^{r+t+s})_\infty  
  = ∏_{k=0}^{∞} (1 + ε^{\,k} q^{\,r+k(r+t+s)}).

Candidate 2: (-q^r ; q^{r+t})_\infty · (- ε q^s ; q^s)_\infty  
  = [∏_{k=0}^{∞} (1 + q^{\,r+k(r+t)})] · [∏_{m=0}^{∞} (1 + ε q^{\,s+m s})].

The first product runs over a single index with step (r+t+s); the second is a product of two independent Pochhammer products with steps (r+t) and s.  
Already for, say, r = t = s = 1 and ε = 1,

• Candidate 1 contains the single factor (1+q) once,  
• Candidate 2 contains (1+q) twice (one from each product),

so the two expressions are not the same. No general identity equates these forms for arbitrary non-negative integers r,t,s and ε = ±1.

Hence the two candidates are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

The expressions inside the logarithms are algebraically identical:

(1 + c²/σ₁²)/(1 + c²/σ₂²)
= ((σ₁² + c²)/σ₁²) ÷ ((σ₂² + c²)/σ₂²)
= (σ₂² (σ₁² + c²)) / (σ₁² (σ₂² + c²))

This is exactly the argument of the logarithm in Candidate 2. Both candidates also share the same prefactor ½ log( · ). Hence the two candidates give the same formula.

Both candidates give the same pair of expressions:

• ε′ : Candidate 1 uses “log(1 + p(e^ε − 1))”; Candidate 2 uses “ln(1 + p(e^ε − 1))”.  
  In the context of mathematics and differential-privacy literature, “log” without a base usually denotes the natural logarithm, so “log” and “ln” are equivalent here.

Both answers provide a complexity classification for each of the two sub-questions.

Sub-question (a):
• Candidate 1: “$\EXP$-complete”  
• Candidate 2: “EXPTIME-complete”

Sub-question (b):
• Candidate 1: “$\P$”  
• Candidate 2: “P”

In standard complexity-theory notation, EXP = EXPTIME, and P = $\P$. Hence the two candidates give identical answers for both (a) and (b).

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give two answers, matching the two sub-questions.

Sub-answer (a):
• Candidate 1: “$\EXP$-complete”  
• Candidate 2: “EXPTIME”

In standard complexity theory, EXP (or $\EXP$) and EXPTIME denote the same deterministic exponential-time class, so these are equivalent. (The “-complete” suffix in Candidate 1 only states completeness with respect to that class; Candidate 2 simply names the class, but the decision problem’s complexity class is the same. Because both are describing the complexity of the decision problem itself, the presence or absence of the word “complete” does not change the predicted class; both indicate EXPTIME.)

Sub-answer (b):
• Candidate 1: “$\P$”  
• Candidate 2: “P”

These are identical.

Thus every required sub-answer coincides.

The two candidate formulas for σ_sum²(C,C) are structurally different.

• Candidate 1 coefficient of σ_element² is n(n-2)/(2(n-3)); Candidate 2’s coefficient is n.

• Candidate 1 subtracts (1/((n-1)(n-3))) Σ ⟨R_k, ĤC⟩² (sum of squares).  
  Candidate 2 subtracts (1/n)(Σ ⟨R_k, ĤC⟩)² (square of sum).

These are different mathematical expressions for general n and general inner-product values. Hence the predictions are not equivalent.
The two candidates give different explicit formulas for σ_sum²(C,C):

• Candidate 1:  σ_sum² = [n(n – 2)]/[2(n – 3)] σ_element²  –  1/[(n – 1)(n – 3)] ∑⟨R_k, Ĉ⟩²

• Candidate 2:  σ_sum² = (1/n) ∑⟨R_k, Ĉ⟩² – ( (1/n) ∑⟨R_k, Ĉ⟩ )²

Candidate 1 involves σ_element² with non-trivial coefficients, whereas Candidate 2 contains no σ_element² term and has a different combination of the inner-product sums. The two expressions are therefore not the same (no algebraic manipulation can equate them without introducing additional unstated identities).

Hence the answers are inequivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give completely different algebraic formulas for σ_sum²(C,C).  
The coefficients in front of σ_element²(C,C) differ ( n²  vs  n(n−2)/(2(n−3)) ) and the coefficients in front of the summation term differ (+1 vs −1/[(n−1)(n−3)]). These expressions cannot be transformed into each other for general n, so they are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different coefficients for each fixed l in the outer sum.

• Candidate 2 coefficient: (–1)^{l+1} · l = (–1)^{l–1} · l

Although the sign factor (–1)^{l–1} matches, 2^{l–1} is generally not equal to l (only for l = 1,2 do they coincide numerically, and they differ for l ≥ 3). Hence the two expressions are not the same identity for general k and l.

Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two expressions are not algebraically identical.

Taking \(q = 3\) as a test case:

• Candidate 1 gives  
 \(P = \dfrac{q}{\binom{q}{2}}\!\left(1-\dfrac{\sum_{i=0}^{q-2}(-1)^i\binom{q}{i}(q-i)^u}{q^{\,u}}\right)\)  
  = \(1-\dfrac{3^u-3\cdot2^u}{3^u}=3\left(\dfrac{2}{3}\right)^u\).

• Candidate 2 gives  
 \(P=\left(\dfrac{q-2}{q}\right)^u=\left(\dfrac13\right)^u\).

Since \(3\left(\dfrac{2}{3}\right)^u\neq\left(\dfrac13\right)^u\) for any positive integer \(u\), the two candidates are unequal.

The two candidates give different mathematical expressions.

This sums |𝓧_ℓ| over an entire congruence class modulo (t+1) and then takes the largest such sum.

This takes only the single largest |𝓧_ℓ|.

In general these quantities are not the same (the first can be strictly larger because it may add several |𝓧_ℓ|’s). Hence the candidates are not equivalent.

The two proposed formulas for V are

Candidate 1: V = (1 − ∏ p_i) / ∑ ((1 − p_i)/p_i)

Candidate 2: V = 1 / ∑ (1/p_i)

To be equivalent we would need

(1 − ∏ p_i) · ∑ (1/p_i) = ∑ ((1 − p_i)/p_i).

But the right-hand side equals ∑ (1/p_i) − n (where n = |S|), whereas the left-hand side equals (1 − ∏ p_i) · ∑ (1/p_i). These two expressions are not generally equal (they coincide only in the trivial case n = 1). Therefore the two candidates give different formulas for V and are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different explicit expressions.

• Candidate 1: gpack = d₂·d₃·…·dᵣ (a simple product of the side lengths except d₁).

• Candidate 2: gpack = gpack(P_{d₂} ⊠ P_{d₃} ⊠ … ⊠ P_{dᵣ}) (the same graph invariant of the product that omits the first factor, left unevaluated).

Unless the invariant gpack of a product of paths always equals the plain numerical product of the path lengths involved (which is generally false—for example, for a single path Pₙ the invariant is not generally n), the two formulas will differ for many admissible choices of d₂,…,dᵣ (e.g., d₂ = 3). Therefore the answers are not equivalent.

Candidate 1: {IPC, Sm, GSc, LC, KC, Bd₂, CPC}

Only four items coincide (IPC, LC, KC, CPC/CL). The remaining three items of each list do not match and are not obviously synonymous.  
Since the required lists are not identical, the two answers are not equivalent (Rule 2 & Rule 3).

The question asks for one count and a complete list of logics.  
Although both candidates give the same count (“7”), their actual lists differ:

Candidate 1: {IPC, Sm, GSc, LC, KC, Bd₂, CPC}  
Candidate 2: {IPC, CPC, LC, KC, LC ∨ KC, BD₂, G₃}

• Candidate 1 includes “Sm” and “GSc,” which do not appear in Candidate 2.  
• Candidate 2 includes “LC ∨ KC” and “G₃,” which do not appear in Candidate 1.  
Even allowing for possible notational variants (e.g., “BD₂” vs “Bd₂”), the sets are not the same.

Hence the two answers are not equivalent.

We compare the two proposed expansion constants:

Candidate 1: λ / (1 – λ)

Candidate 2: (d λ + 1) / (d + 1)

Candidate 1 depends only on λ, whereas Candidate 2 depends on both λ and the dimension d. Since d is a variable parameter of the complex and is not fixed or eliminated, the two formulas cannot coincide for all possible values of d and λ. Therefore the two predictions are not equivalent.
The two candidates give different formulas:

• Candidate 1: λ / (1 − λ)  
• Candidate 2: (d − 1) λ

These expressions are generally not equal (they coincide only for the very special value λ = 1 − 1/(d − 1), not in general). Therefore, the answers are not equivalent.

Both candidates give a formula for the size of a largest subset of {0,…,n} whose chosen indices differ by more than t, but the two formulas do not coincide.

Take n = 2 and t = 1.  
• Candidate 1 requires ℓ ≡ ⌊n/2⌋ (mod t+1) = 1 (mod 2); the admissible ℓ are {1}. So its size is 1.  
• Candidate 2 allows any set of indices whose pairwise distance exceeds 1 and then sums over those k. A maximal such set is {0,2}, whose size is 2.

Because the two candidates give different cardinalities in this example, their answers are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Candidate 1: 
C = (1 − 1/N) / [1 − 1 / N^{K/D}]

Candidate 2: 
C = (1 − D/N) / [1 − (D/N)^{K/D}]

With N = D + 1 (as stated in the problem):

• Numerators  
 Candidate 1: 1 − 1/N = (N − 1)/N = D / N  
 Candidate 2: 1 − D/N = (N − D)/N = 1 / N  

 These are equal only when D = 1; for general D they differ.

• Denominators  
 Candidate 1: 1 − 1/N^{K/D}  
 Candidate 2: 1 − (D/N)^{K/D} = 1 − (D/(D+1))^{K/D}  

 Except for D = 1, these are different factors.

Since, for general D (D > 1), both the numerator and the denominator differ, the two expressions are not algebraically identical. Therefore the two candidate answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give completely different algebraic expressions for the game value.

•  Candidate 1:  ((k-b)/(k+1)) p^{\,n-a+1} + ((b+1)/(k+1)) p^{\,n-a}
  = p^{\,n-a}\,[((k-b)/(k+1)) p + (b+1)/(k+1)].

•  Candidate 2:  (1-(1-p)^a)^{\,k+1-b} · (1-(1-p)^{a+1})^{\,b-1}.

Substituting simple integer values (e.g. k = 1, a = 1, p = 0.5):

 Candidate 1 → 0.375,  
 Candidate 2 → 0.333…

The two results differ, and algebraically the formulas are not transformable into one another.

Thus the candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give fundamentally different expressions for k.

• Candidate 1 provides a very explicit, enormous formula involving exp (·) and powers of p and ξ.  
• Candidate 2 only states an asymptotic bound “\(k = p^{O(1/\xi^{2})}\),” i.e., that k is at most polynomial in p with exponent proportional to \(1/\xi^{2}\).

These descriptions are not algebraically or numerically identical, nor can one be derived directly from the other without extra unstated assumptions. Therefore, by the rules (notably Rule 6 on type mismatch and completeness), the answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give explicit, but different, formulas for \(E_n\):

• Candidate 1: \(E_n = 2^{\lfloor (n-2)/4 \rfloor + 1}\)  
• Candidate 2: \(E_n = n!\,\sum_{k=0}^{n}\dfrac{(-1)^k}{k!}\)

These expressions are plainly not the same function of \(n\). For instance, at \(n=2\), Candidate 1 gives \(2\) while Candidate 2 gives \(1\). Hence the answers are inequivalent (Rule 8: different explicit formulas that are not algebraically identical).

Both candidates give a formula of the form

σ_i = (1/2) · (something depending on sin).

Candidate 1: σ_i = ½ |csc(θ)| = ½ |1/sin θ|  
Candidate 2: σ_i = ½ · 1/sin θ

where θ = (2i − 1)π/(4ℓ + 2).

For i = 1,…,ℓ, θ lies strictly between 0 and π/2, so sin θ is strictly positive. Therefore |1/sin θ| = 1/sin θ, and the absolute-value bars in Candidate 1 have no effect. Thus the two expressions are identical for all allowed indices.

Hence the two candidates are equivalent.

For general n and t these quantities are not the same (e.g., n = 3, t = 2 gives 3 vs. 8⁄3). Hence the answers are inequivalent.
The two candidates give different closed-form expressions:

• Candidate 1:  ∑_{ℓ=0, ℓ≡⌊n/2⌋ (mod t+1)}^n C(n,ℓ)  
(This is a sum over roughly 1/(t+1) of all binomial coefficients.)

(This is just the single central binomial coefficient.)

These expressions are not the same (e.g., for t=1 and n=5, Candidate 1 gives 16 whereas Candidate 2 gives 10). Hence they are inequivalent.

which is not generally guaranteed by the information given. Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two expressions give different numerical values in general.

Set them equal:
(k − 1)n / 2 = n(k + 1) − 2  
⇒ (k − 1)n = 2n(k + 1) − 4  
⇒ n(k − 1 − 2k − 2) + 4 = 0  
⇒ n(−k − 3) + 4 = 0  
⇒ n(k + 3) = 4.

For positive integers k and even n (with k ≥ 2), this equation cannot be satisfied. Hence the two formulas are not algebraically the same (except in impossible/non-integer cases).

Therefore, Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different algebraic expressions:

Candidate 1: ½ (3 p⁶ − 9 p⁵ + 22 p³ − 16 p² − 8 p + 8)    (degree 6 polynomial)

Candidate 2: (p − 1)⁴ = p⁴ − 4 p³ + 6 p² − 4 p + 1    (degree 4 polynomial)

Since these polynomials are of different degrees and their coefficients do not match, they cannot be identical for all p. Thus the two answers are not equivalent.

The question asks for two specific values of \(\optaccessval(\varphi)\).  
Both candidates supply a pair of values, but they differ in the second case:

• When \(\varphi\) is satisfiable: both give \(k\).  
• When \(\varphi\) is not satisfiable:  
 – Candidate 1 gives \(\lfloor k/2\rfloor\).  
 – Candidate 2 gives \(0\).

Unless \(k\) is restricted to \(0\) or \(1\) (which the problem statement does not say), these expressions are generally not the same (e.g., for \(k=2\): \(\lfloor k/2\rfloor = 1\neq 0\)). Therefore, the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different explicit formulas for g(n,m):

• Candidate 1:  
 g(n,m)= m (if m ≤ n)  
 g(n,m)= 2m − n (if n < m < 2ⁿ)

• Candidate 2:  
 g(n,m)= ⌈log₂ m⌉ (in both regions)

For many values (e.g., n=10, m=5) these outputs differ (5 vs. 3), so the answers are not the same. Hence the predictions are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different explicit formulas for the two parameter ranges.

Range 1 (m ≤ n):
• Candidate 1: g = m  
• Candidate 2: g = ⌈log₂ m⌉  
These expressions are not equal in general (e.g., m = 5 gives 5 vs 3).

Range 2 (n < m < 2ⁿ):
• Candidate 1: g = 2m − n  
• Candidate 2: g = n  
Again, these differ for almost every permissible (n,m).

Since the formulas disagree in both pieces of the domain, the answers are not equivalent.
The two candidates give different explicit formulas for g(n,m).

Example: take n = 10, m = 5 (so m ≤ n).

• Candidate 1: g = m = 5  
• Candidate 2: g = ⌈log₂ m⌉ = ⌈log₂ 5⌉ = 3

Since the numerical results differ, the formulas cannot be equivalent. The same discrepancy occurs in the other region n < m < 2ⁿ.

The formulas given by the two candidates are not the same:

  – Candidate 1 gives the Catalan number C₂ = 2.  
  – Candidate 2 gives binom(2·3 − 3, 3 − 2) = binom(3,1) = 3.  

Since the expressions disagree, the two candidates are not equivalent.

The question requests two pieces of information:  
1. A formula for arbitrary m × n Ferrers diagrams (with m ≥ n ≥ 2).  
2. The specialization to n × n diagrams.

Candidate 1 supplies both:
• General formula: \(\dfrac{m-n+1}{m}\binom{m+n-2}{\,n-1\,}\).  
• n × n case: Catalan number \(C_{n-1}=\dfrac1n\binom{2n-2}{\,n-1\,}\).

Candidate 2 gives only a single expression, \(\binom{2n-4}{\,n-2\,}\), with no general m,n formula.  
Moreover, \(\binom{2n-4}{\,n-2\,}\) is not equal to the Catalan number \(C_{n-1}\) for all n (e.g. at n = 4 it yields 6 while \(C_3=5\)).

Thus the two candidates do not provide the same answers, and Candidate 2 is incomplete relative to the question’s requirements.

The two proposed results are completely different Meijer-G representations.

1. The overall prefactors differ:  
   • Candidate 1 has 1/(4 π^{3/2});  
   • Candidate 2 has a^{-s}.  
   These factors cannot be converted into each other by any simple change of variables or Meijer-G identity.

2. The Meijer-G functions themselves have different parameters:  
   • Candidate 1: G_{3,5}^{5,2}(a^{2}/4 | … ).  
   • Candidate 2: G_{2,3}^{3,1}(a | … ).  
   The orders (p, q, m, n) and the arguments (a^{2}/4 versus a) do not match, nor do the lists of upper and lower parameters.

3. No standard property of Meijer-G functions turns one expression with these parameter sets and argument a^{2}/4 into the other with argument a and a completely different prefactor.

Because the expressions are not the same function (even up to a constant factor or a simple rescaling of the argument) the two answers give inequivalent results for the integral.

The two candidates give the following numerical quantities  

Candidate 1: π  

Candidate 2: π [erf(eᵉ)]²  

For the real number E = eᵉ ≈ 15.15426,  
erf(E) = 1 − O(10⁻¹⁰⁰); hence [erf(E)]² = 1 − O(10⁻¹⁰⁰).  
Therefore  

π [erf(E)]² = π − O(10⁻¹⁰⁰).  

The difference between the two candidates is on the order of 10⁻¹⁰⁰, so the two values agree to far more than the 6 significant digits required by Rule 4. Thus, within the tolerance set by the rules, the two answers are considered the same.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two expressions represent the same quantity:

Candidate 1: (16 π / 3) (1 − 1/√2)
     = 2 · (8 π / 3) (1 − 1/√2)
     = (8 π / 3) (2 − 2/√2)
     = (8 π / 3) (2 − √2)

Candidate 2: (8 π / 3)(2 − √2)

Thus Candidate 1 simplifies exactly to Candidate 2. They are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The only difference between the two candidates is the notation “log (3)” versus “ln 3”.  
In typical mathematical usage—especially in calculus and analysis contexts where “ln” is explicitly used as well—“log” without a base is understood to be the natural logarithm (base e). Thus

log (3) = ln 3.

Both candidates then represent exactly the same numerical value:

Candidate 1: log (3) − 1/4  
Candidate 2: ln 3 − 1/4

Hence the two answers are mathematically identical.
The two answers are

Candidate 1:  log(3) − ¼  
Candidate 2:  ln 3 − ¼

“ln 3” is unambiguously the natural logarithm.  
“log(3)” is ambiguous: in mathematics it can denote either the natural logarithm or a base-10 logarithm (especially in problems already involving powers of 10, as here). Because different bases give different numerical values, multiple reasonable interpretations exist. Hence Candidate 1 leaves an essential ambiguity that Candidate 2 does not have.

Since the omission of the logarithm base in Candidate 1 causes potential confusion and the two expressions are not guaranteed to be the same, the answers are not equivalent.

The quantity being asked for is a vector in ℝ² (the integral of x^⊥ over the unit circle).  

• Candidate 1 answers with the scalar “0”.  
• Candidate 2 answers with the vector “(0, 0)”.

A scalar zero and a zero vector are different mathematical objects; there is no explicit indication that Candidate 1’s “0” is meant to denote a vector.  
Under Rule 6 (type mismatch) they are therefore not considered equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both answers represent the vanishing result of the integral.  
Although Candidate 1 writes simply “0” (a scalar symbol) and Candidate 2 explicitly writes the zero vector “(0, 0)”, in mathematical writing it is standard to denote the zero element of any vector space just by “0” when the context makes the type clear.  
Here the integrand is a vector field, so the context implies that “0” in Candidate 1 means the zero vector. Thus the two responses convey the same result.

The two expressions are clearly different:

1/24 + (1/8) ln 2 + (1/8) ln π − (3/4) ln A.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give a single formula intended to return the same quantity – the (unsigned) count of isolated real zeros of f on [a,b].

•  Candidate 1 writes that number as a winding/argument‐change expression involving  
  f, f′, f″ (with a final “round’’ to an integer).

•  Candidate 2 writes it as the distributional identity  
     N = ∫ₐᵇ δ(f(x)) |f′(x)| dx ,  
  which is the standard Dirac-delta way of counting isolated roots (each root contributes 1).

For a smooth function with isolated zeros (the setting of the problem), both expressions evaluate to the same integer N for every admissible f. They are just two analytically different but mathematically equivalent ways to compute the same count.

Hence the two predictions are equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

The question asks for a single numerical value (the maximum deviation) expressed in angular measure.

Candidate 1: “6 min”  
• Unit: arcminutes.  
• Convert to arcseconds: 6 × 60 = 360 arcsec.

Candidate 2: “≈ 355 seconds of arc”  
• Unit: arcseconds.  
• Value: 355 arcsec.

Comparing the two numerical results in the same unit (arcseconds):  
360 arcsec vs. 355 arcsec differ by 5 arcsec.  
Per Rule 4, real-number answers must match to 6 significant digits to be considered the same; 360.000 and 355.000 do not match.

Therefore, the two candidates are not equivalent.

Both candidates give a single numerical result for the range, but:

• Candidate 1: “202 km” (explicitly kilometres).  
• Candidate 2: “201398.5” (no unit stated).  
  – If interpreted as metres → 201 398.5 m = 201.3985 km, which differs from 202.000 km at the third significant digit (fails Rule 4).  
  – If interpreted as kilometres → 201 398.5 km, vastly different.

Because Candidate 2 omits the unit (Rule 1) and, under any reasonable interpretation, its value is not identical to Candidate 1’s to 6 significant digits (Rule 4), the two answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different physical quantities.

• Candidate 1: “0.7854 s” – a time interval (the period).

• Candidate 2: “4/π Hz” ≈ 1.27324 s⁻¹ – a frequency.

Period and frequency are reciprocals, not the same quantity. Although 1 / 0.7854 s ≈ 1.27324 Hz (numerically matching Candidate 2), Candidate 1 explicitly states the answer in seconds, not in hertz, so the two answers are not the same prediction.

The two candidates give numeric answers for the amplitude, but in different units.

1. Convert Candidate 1 from feet to inches:
   0.18162 ft × 12 in/ft = 2.17944 in.

2. Candidate 2 already gives the value in inches:
   √19 / 2 in ≈ 4.358898944 / 2 ≈ 2.179449472 in.

3. Compare to six significant digits (Rule 4):
   • Candidate 1: 2.17944 0 in  (pad with a zero to reach six significant digits → 2.17944 0)  
   • Candidate 2: 2.17945 in (rounded from 2.17944947…)

These differ in the 6th significant digit (…440 vs …450).  
Hence the two answers are not identical to six-significant-digit precision, so they are not equivalent.

The question asks for a single numerical ratio.  
Both candidates give one numerical value and no units.

• Candidate 1: “4.16 $10^{42}$”  
• Candidate 2: “4.16 × 10^{42}”

Candidate 1 clearly intends scientific notation, using LaTeX math mode for the power of ten but omitting the explicit “×”. This is a common formatting slip; it still denotes 4.16 × 10^{42}.  
Thus both answers represent the same number: 4.16000 × 10^{42} (identical through at least six significant digits, satisfying Rule 4).

Therefore, the two predictions are equivalent.

The question asks for the electric field (a vector quantity).  
Candidate 2 supplies both the magnitude (2.50 × 10⁴ N/C) and the direction (“radially outward”), while Candidate 1 gives only the magnitude (2.50 × 10⁴ N/C) with no direction indicated. Because an essential part of a vector answer (the direction) is missing from Candidate 1, the two responses are not equivalent per Rule 2/Rule 9.

Reasoning:

• Both candidates give a single numerical multiple of L, so the units (length) match – we just need to compare the numerical factors.

• Candidate 1: 2.72 L  → numerical factor = 2.720000 (to 6 significant digits).

• Candidate 2: (5 + √10)/3 L  
  √10 ≈ 3.162277660…  
  (5 + √10)/3 ≈ 2.72075922 → to 6 significant digits: 2.72076.

• Compare the two factors digit-by-digit up to 6 significant digits (Rule 4):
  – Candidate 1: 2.72000  
  – Candidate 2: 2.72076  
  They differ at the 5th and 6th significant digits.

Since they do not match to 6 significant digits, the two answers are not equivalent.

According to Rule 2, the question effectively has two requested items:

1. The calculated energy per mole.  
2. A comparison of that energy with 400 kJ /mol.

• Candidate 2 supplies both items (“399 kJ/mol; nearly equal to 400 kJ/mol”).  
• Candidate 1 supplies only the first item (“399 kJ/mol”) and omits the explicit comparison.

Because Candidate 1 fails to provide one of the required parts, the two answers are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The question has two tasks:  
(1) give the energy per mole of 300-nm photons, and  
(2) compare that value with the reference 400 kJ mol⁻¹.

Candidate 1 only supplies the energy “399 kJ mol⁻¹” but omits the required comparison.  
Candidate 2 supplies the same energy “399 kJ mol⁻¹” and explicitly states the comparison “comparable to 400 kJ mol⁻¹.”

Because Candidate 1 fails to provide one of the required pieces of information, while Candidate 2 provides both, the two answers are not equivalent (Rule 2).

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

Moreover, Candidate 2 does not specify units, introducing additional ambiguity per Rule 1.

Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.

The Bohr magneton is  
μ_B = 9.274 01 × 10⁻²⁴ J T⁻¹.

Candidate 2 gives √3 μ_B ⇒ √3 × 9.274 01 × 10⁻²⁴ ≈ 1.60574 × 10⁻²³ J T⁻¹.

Candidate 1 is 1.61 × 10⁻²³ J T⁻¹, which expressed to six significant digits is 1.61000 × 10⁻²³ J T⁻¹.

Comparing the two numbers at six significant digits (Rule 4):
1.61000 ≠ 1.60574.

Because the values differ within the first six significant digits, the two answers are not equivalent.

• Candidate 2 → 0.0181924

We compare the numerical values.

Candidate 1: 0.0182

Product ≈ 0.0181920 (1.81920 × 10⁻²)

They differ at the 4th significant digit, so they are not identical to 6 significant digits. Hence, the two candidates are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The question requests TWO separate values of the limit:  
• one for the case r = s,  
• one for the case r ≠ s.

Candidate 1 supplies both required cases:  
– limit = φ(r) when r = s,  
– limit = 0 when r ≠ s.

Candidate 2 gives only a single value φ(r) with no distinction, thus omitting the r ≠ s case.

Since Candidate 2 does not provide all answers required by the problem, the two candidates are not equivalent (Rule 2).

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different formulas.

• Candidate 1 assigns rank 1 whenever \(C_{(1)}(M)\neq 0\) (e.g. for a pure vector).  
• Candidate 2 looks only at the highest non-zero grade in \(T=M^\dagger M\).  For a pure vector \(M\), \(T\) is a scalar, so every \(C_{(j)}(T)\) with \(j\ge 1\) is zero; Candidate 2 would then return 0 (or be undefined), not 1.

Hence the two expressions cannot agree in general.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two expressions are not the same.

•  Candidate 1 gives
  F₁(z,q)= (−zq; q²)∞ ∕ (zq; q)∞ ,
 whose constant (z⁰) coefficient equals 1.

•  Candidate 2 gives
  F₂(z,q)= (q; q)∞⁻¹ ∑_{k∈ℤ} z^k q^{k²} ,
 whose constant coefficient equals 1 ∕ (q; q)∞ ≠ 1.

Since the very first coefficient already differs, the two series (and thus the generating functions) cannot be equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give exactly the same criterion:

• If the series \( \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \psi(n)(\log n)^{k-1} \) converges, they both say \( \lambda_k(W_k^\times(\psi)) = 0\).

• If that series diverges, they both say \( \lambda_k(W_k^\times(\psi)) = 1\).

Hence their answers are equivalent. 

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give exactly the same criterion:

• Both say λₖ(Wₖ^×(ψ)) = 0 when the series S = Σ ψ(n)(log n)^{k−1} converges (is finite).  
• Both say λₖ(Wₖ^×(ψ)) = 1 when the same series diverges (is infinite).

Thus they are equivalent.
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give the identical set of solutions, namely  
\[(x,y,z) = (\pm 3,\;\pm 5,\;11).\]

They differ only in wording, not in the mathematical content. Hence the two answers are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different algebraic expressions for \(\mathcal R_\star\).

• Candidate 1: \(\log_2\!\Bigl(1+\dfrac{\overline\gamma_b\,g_b\bigl[1+\overline\gamma_e\,g_e(1-\overline\rho)\bigr]}{1+\overline\gamma_e\,g_e}\Bigr)\)

• Candidate 2: \(\log_2(1+\overline\gamma_b)-\log_2(1+\overline\gamma_e)\)

Candidate 2 contains no \(g_b\), \(g_e\), or \(\overline\rho\), whereas the question explicitly asks for the answer in terms of those variables. Hence the two answers are not mathematically or symbolically equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

The only common relations in the two proposed rings are  
• μ η = 0  
• ν θ = 0  

Candidate 1 imposes an additional relation  
 μ² + η² − ν² − η² = μ² − ν² = 0,  
whereas Candidate 2 does not.  
That extra relation is not a formal consequence of (μ η, ν θ) in general, so the two quotient rings are different.

The two candidates give different algebraic expressions:

• Candidate 1:  r n + m − 2  
• Candidate 2:  2 n (r − 1)  = 2 n r − 2 n

For these to be equivalent we would need  
r n + m − 2 = 2 n r − 2 n,  
which simplifies to  
m = n (r − 2) + 2.

This condition is not generally satisfied for arbitrary integers m, n, r as specified in the problem. Hence the two answers are not the same in general.

Candidate 1 gives

The two expressions are

Candidate 1: cₙ,ₛ · (A² + 16 ξ²)^{−(n+s+1)/2}

Candidate 2: cₙ,ₛ · π · (ξ² + (A/2)²)^{−(n+s+1)/2}
             = cₙ,ₛ · π · (A²/4 + ξ²)^{−(n+s+1)/2}
             = cₙ,ₛ · π · 4^{(n+s+1)/2} · (A² + 4 ξ²)^{−(n+s+1)/2}

Comparing the factors inside the parentheses:

• Candidate 1 has (A² + 16 ξ²).
• Candidate 2 (after factoring) has (A² + 4 ξ²) multiplied by an overall constant 4^{(n+s+1)/2}·π.

Because the ξ² coefficients (16 vs 4) differ, the two expressions cannot be made identical by any overall constant factor; they would only coincide for special values of ξ (e.g., ξ = 0), not in general. Hence the answers are not equivalent.
The two expressions inside the parentheses are different:

• Candidate 1 uses A² + 16 ξ²  
• Candidate 2 uses ξ² + (A/2)² = ξ² + A²/4

Because these differ by factors that depend on both A and ξ, and the prefactor c_{n,s} is the same fixed constant in each answer, the overall results are not the same functions of the parameters.

The two answers are not stated in the same form.

• Candidate 1 fixes a single residue class (the one containing ⌊n/2⌋ mod (t + 1)) and sums the q-binomial coefficients in that class.

• Candidate 2 takes the maximum, over all residue classes r = 0,…,t, of those same sums.

Because Candidate 1 does not include the “max over r” that appears in Candidate 2, the two formulas can differ whenever some other residue class gives a strictly larger sum than the one that contains ⌊n/2⌋.  Hence the two expressions are not guaranteed to be equal in general.

• Candidate 2 states the sum over a residue class r but leaves r arbitrary (“for some integer r with 0 ≤ r ≤ t”).

Because Candidate 2 does not specify the same fixed residue class as Candidate 1 (indeed, it allows any of them), the two formulas do not coincide in general. Therefore the answers are not equivalent.

The question asks for a single explicit formula for β₁(J_G) in terms of the listed parameters.  

• Candidate 1 supplies a long expression that depends on n, m, the sum of binomial terms over degrees of vertices not in K_m, etc.  
• Candidate 2 supplies the very simple value (m − 1)(m − 2)/2, which involves only m and ignores n and all of the various degree terms.

The two formulas clearly differ; there is no algebraic way for Candidate 1’s expression (which varies with n and individual vertex degrees) to equal Candidate 2’s simple function of m alone for every admissible graph. Hence the predictions are not equivalent.

These formulas clearly cannot be algebraically identical for arbitrary values of the parameters.

The two candidates give different formulas:

For n = 8 (as a simple check with n ≥ 4):

Since the results differ (4 vs. 5), the two formulas cannot be identical for all n. Hence the predictions are not equivalent.

Both candidates give expressions that share the same elementary prefactors  
(2π)^{n/2} (β/2)^{-[β n(n-1)/4 + n/2]}.

For the remaining gamma-function part,

Candidate 2: ∏_{j=1}^n Γ(1 + jβ/2) / Γ(1 + β/2)  
     = ∏_{j=1}^n [(jβ/2) Γ(jβ/2)] / [(β/2) Γ(β/2)]  
     = n! (β/2)^n ∏_{j=1}^n Γ(jβ/2) / [(β/2)^n Γ(β/2)^n]  
     = n! Γ(β/2)^{-n} ∏_{j=1}^n Γ(jβ/2).

This equals exactly the gamma-factor appearing in Candidate 1:
 n! Γ(β/2)^{-n} ∏_{j=1}^n Γ(jβ/2).

Hence the two formulas are identical:

Candidate 1 = Candidate 2.

Candidate 1 gives  
σ(G) = (m n p – 1)! · [∏_{i=1}^{m+n+p-1} b_i] ÷ [∏_{i=1}^{m-1} b_i  · ∏_{i=1}^{n-1} b_i · ∏_{i=1}^{p-1} b_i].

Candidate 2 gives  
σ(G) = (m n p)! ÷ [∏_{i=1}^{m+n+p-1} b_i].

These two formulas differ in several clear ways:

1. Factorial: Candidate 1 has (mnp – 1)! whereas Candidate 2 has (mnp)!.
2. Placement of the product ∏ b_i: it is in the numerator for Candidate 1 and in the denominator for Candidate 2 (they are reciprocals).
3. Candidate 1 contains additional factors in its denominator (products over the first m–1, n–1, and p–1 indices) that are completely absent in Candidate 2.

Because of these discrepancies, the two expressions cannot be algebraically identical for general m, n, p. Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different formulas.

Candidate 1:  σ(G) = [(mnp − 1)! ⋅ ∏_{i=1}^{m+n+p−1} b_i] / [∏_{i=1}^{m−1} b_i ⋅ ∏_{i=1}^{n−1} b_i ⋅ ∏_{i=1}^{p−1} b_i]  (plus an alternative simplified form).

Candidate 2:  σ(G) = ∏_{i=1}^{m+n+p−1} b_i.

Candidate 2 lacks the factorial terms and the denominator factors appearing in Candidate 1, so the two expressions disagree for generic m,n,p. Hence they are not equivalent.

The two candidates give completely different formulae:

1. Candidate 1:      \|\widetilde{\mathbf{H}}^{\mu,\nu}_{\alpha,\beta}\| =  \dfrac{p}{\alpha^{1/p}\,\beta^{1/p'}}\!\left(\dfrac{1}{1+\mu}+\dfrac{1}{p-1-\nu}\right)

2. Candidate 2:      \|\widetilde{\mathbf{H}}^{\mu,\nu}_{\alpha,\beta}\| = B\!\left(\alpha+\mu+\frac1{p'},\,\beta+\nu+\frac1p\right)

The first is a rational combination of the parameters; the second is a Beta-function value depending on different combinations of the parameters. They are not algebraically the same, nor numerically convertible by a simple identity. Therefore, the answers are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give completely different mathematical expressions for the operator norm.

• Candidate 1:   \|\widetilde{\mathbf{H}}^{\mu,\nu}_{\alpha,\beta}\| =  \dfrac{p}{\alpha^{1/p}\,\beta^{1/p'}}\Bigl(\dfrac{1}{1+\mu}+\dfrac{1}{\,p-1-\nu}\Bigr)

• Candidate 2:   \|\widetilde{\mathbf{H}}^{\mu,\nu}_{\alpha,\beta}\| =
   \dfrac{\Gamma\!\bigl(\dfrac{1+\mu}{p}\bigr)\,
          \Gamma\!\bigl(\dfrac{1+\nu}{p'}\bigr)}
        {\Gamma\!\bigl(\dfrac{1+\mu}{p}+\dfrac{1+\nu}{p'}\bigr)}
   \,\cdot\,
   \dfrac{1}{\alpha+\beta-\dfrac{\mu+\nu}{p}-\dfrac{1}{p'}}

These formulas are not algebraically or functionally equivalent (one involves gamma‐functions, the other a simple rational combination). Therefore the two answers are not the same.

The two candidates give different formulas for both requested quantities:

   • Candidate 1: \( \dfrac{S_N-1}{2(N-1)}\)  
   • Candidate 2: \( \dfrac{1}{S_N}\)

These expressions are not algebraically the same (they do not reduce to one another for general \(N\) and \(S_N\)). Therefore, the candidates are not equivalent.
The two candidates give different explicit formulas for both 
1) the minimum loss \(L_{\text{min}}\) and  
2) the parameter \(\epsilon\).

Candidate 1 includes factors \(\frac{N}{2(N-1)}\) in \(L_{\text{min}}\) and \(\frac{1}{2(N-1)}\) in \(\epsilon\), whereas Candidate 2 lacks these factors.  
These two sets of expressions coincide only for special (non-generic) values of \(N\) (e.g., \(N=2\) for \(L_{\text{min}}\)), but the question is stated for general \(N\). Hence, the answers are not mathematically equivalent.

The numerical value of Candidate 1 is  
−(log 3)/(log 5) ≈ −0.682606.  

Candidate 2 gives −0.6826, which we interpret as −0.682600 when extended to six significant digits.

Comparing the two numbers to six significant digits:
• Candidate 1: −0.682606  
• Candidate 2: −0.682600  

They differ in the 6th significant digit (…06 vs …00).  
Hence, according to Rule 4, the two answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different formulas:

• Candidate 2: r(G) · (ms)^{α(G)}

These expressions depend on the parameters m, s, weights w(x_j), and the binomial coefficient in completely different ways. Unless very special extra conditions were imposed (e.g., all weights equal 1, L₂(C_i) empty, and s^{α(G)} equaling the binomial coefficient, which is not generally true), the two formulas are not the same.

Therefore, the candidates are not equivalent.

Both candidates give the same rational function.

Candidate 1  
G₁(q) = 1/(1-q) + q²/[(1-q)²(1-q²)]  
    = (1 – q + q³) / [(1-q)³(1+q)]

Candidate 2  
G₂(q) = (q⁵ + 2q⁴ – q² + q + 1) / (1-q²)³  
    = (1 – q + q³)(1+q)² / (1-q²)³   (since (1+q)² = 1 + 2q + q²)

But (1-q²)³ = (1-q)³(1+q)³, so

G₁(q) = (1 – q + q³)(1+q)² / (1-q²)³ = G₂(q).

Thus the two expressions are algebraically identical, hence equivalent.

Candidate 1 gives  
 2 d₍GH₎(λ Δₙ, X) = inf_{D∈𝓓ₙ(X)} max{ diam D, λ – α(D), diam X – λ }.

Candidate 2 gives  
 2 d₍GH₎(λ Δₙ, X) = max{ diam X – λ, diam D – λ + 2 α(D) }.

Differences:

1. Candidate 1 takes an infimum over D∈𝓓ₙ(X); Candidate 2 has no such infimum.
2. The sets inside the max are different: Candidate 1 uses diam D and λ – α(D); Candidate 2 uses diam D – λ + 2 α(D).

Because both the functional form and the presence of the infimum differ, the two expressions cannot be the same.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates are not equivalent.

Candidate 1 states very specific equality conditions:

• Ω must be (up to measure-zero) a ball centered at some point (x₀, ω₀);
• f must be exactly a translation-and-modulation of the fixed Gaussian φ, namely  
  f(x)=c e^{2πixω₀} φ(x−x₀).

Hence the centre of the ball is tied to the translation/modulation parameters of f, and the Gaussian width is the one of φ.

Candidate 2 only says:

• f is “a Gaussian function” (without fixing its width or requiring any particular translation/modulation relation to Ω);
• Ω is “a ball in ℝ²” (without requiring its centre to match anything linked to f).

Because Candidate 2 omits the essential coupling between the centre of Ω and the time-frequency shift parameters of f (and does not fix the Gaussian’s width), it gives strictly weaker conditions than Candidate 1. Therefore the two answers are not the same.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates are not equivalent.

Reasoning:

• Candidate 1 specifies that equality holds precisely when  
  – Ω is (up to null sets) a ball centred at some point (x₀, ω₀); and  
  – f is c e^{2π i x ω₀} φ(x − x₀), i.e. a Gaussian window translated and modulated by (x₀, ω₀).

• Candidate 2 merely says that f is “a Gaussian function’’ and Ω is a ball.  
  It omits the necessary translation/modulation factor e^{2π i x ω₀} and the location (x₀, ω₀) of the ball, so it does not describe exactly the same class of extremisers.

Because Candidate 2 lacks these essential conditions, the answers differ.

The two candidates give different closed-form products.  
To make them match, Candidate 1’s expression would have to equal Candidate 2’s, i.e.

(u³;q³)∞ / (u;q)∞  =  (−u;q)∞(−u²;q)∞(u³;q³)∞

⇒ 1 = (−u;q)∞(−u²;q)∞(u;q)∞.

However  
(−u;q)∞(u;q)∞ = (u²;q²)∞,  
so the right-hand side becomes (u²;q²)∞(−u²;q)∞, which is not identically 1 (a quick numerical check already shows it differs from 1).

Hence the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give explicit closed-form expressions for the same single quantity, so we can directly test algebraic equality (Rules 1, 4, 8).

Candidate 1:  
1 + n + n² + [(n + 1)/2] · C(n + 2, 3)  
 = 1 + n + n² + [(n + 1)/2] · [(n + 2)(n + 1)n / 6]  
 = 1 + n + n² + [(n + 1)²(n + 2)n]/12.

This is a quartic polynomial in n (highest power n⁴).

Candidate 2:  
[(n + 1)(n + 2)]/2  
 = (n² + 3n + 2)/2,

which is only quadratic in n.

Because the degrees (and therefore the values) of these two polynomials differ, the expressions cannot be identical for general n. Hence the two answers are not equivalent.

The question asks for one explicit expression.

There is no general algebraic identity that makes those two expressions identical for all k and t. Hence they are not equivalent.

The two candidates do not give the same distributions.

• Candidate 1 specifies an n-dimensional, zero-mean Gaussian whose covariance matrix is (P/n) Iₙ (so each coordinate has variance P/n and the total second moment ‖X‖² has expectation P).  It likewise chooses Z ~ N(0,(N/n) Iₙ).

• Candidate 2 states simply that X and Z are zero-mean Gaussians with variances P and N, respectively.  This corresponds to a **scalar** (or 1-dimensional) Gaussian with variance P (or, if one tried to interpret it component-wise, each coordinate would have variance P, giving total power nP, which violates the constraint).

Thus, except in the special case n = 1, the two answers describe different covariance structures and are not equivalent.  The question does not restrict n to 1, so the candidates must be regarded as giving different solutions.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates describe different Gaussian distributions:

• Candidate 1: multivariate zero-mean Gaussian with per–dimension variance P/n for X and N/n for Z (total second-moment constraints P and N).

• Candidate 2: zero-mean Gaussian with scalar variance P for X and N for Z (no division by n).

Because the variances differ (except in the special case n = 1, which is not specified) the stated saddle-point distributions are not the same. Hence the answers are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different Narayana numbers.

Candidate 1: \(N(m+n,n)=\frac1{m+n}\binom{m+n}{n}\binom{m+n}{\,n-1}\).

Candidate 2: \(N(m+n,m)=\frac1{m+n}\binom{m+n}{m}\binom{m+n}{\,m-1}\).

Although \(\binom{m+n}{n}=\binom{m+n}{m}\), the second binomial factors differ in general (\(\binom{m+n}{n-1}\) vs. \(\binom{m+n}{m-1}\)). The Narayana numbers satisfy \(N(k,r)=N(k,k-r+1)\), so \(N(m+n,n)=N(m+n,m+1)\), not \(N(m+n,m)\). Hence the two expressions are unequal for generic \(m,n\).

Both candidates give exactly the same product:

• They both take the product over j = 1,…, l (ℓ).  
• Inside, they both have the factor 1 / |Aut_{R_j}(G_j)|.  
• They both multiply by an infinite Euler product ∏_{i=1}^{∞} (1 – p^{-deg(P_j)·i}).  
  (Candidate 1 uses index i, candidate 2 uses k; this is just a dummy index.)

The order of the two factors inside the parentheses is irrelevant (multiplication is commutative), and the symbols i and k denote the same infinite range.

Hence the two expressions are mathematically identical.

Both candidates give an Euler–product expression for the same probability.  
For every fixed prime p and each corank i, the factor appearing in Candidate 1

  p-i² · ∏_{j=i+1}^{n}(1–p^{-j})² / ∏_{j=1}^{n-i}(1–p^{-j})

is exactly the probability that a random n × n matrix over 𝐅_p has corank i, which is

  (# of n × n matrices over 𝐅_p of rank n–i) / p^{n²} .

Summing those probabilities for i = 0,…,k and then taking the product over all primes gives
  ∏_{p} ∑_{r=n-k}^{n} (# of matrices of rank r)/p^{n²},

which is precisely Candidate 2.  Direct checks for several small values of (n,k) (e.g. (1,0), (1,1), (2,1)) confirm that the two formulas coincide.

Thus the two answers are mathematically the same expression written in different algebraic forms.

The two candidate expressions are:

• Candidate 1: (m − 1) n + C_{cc}(H)

• Candidate 2: m C_{cc}(H) + n (m − 1)

Subtracting the first from the second gives  
m C_{cc}(H) + n (m − 1) − [(m − 1) n + C_{cc}(H)]  
= m C_{cc}(H) − C_{cc}(H)  
= (m − 1) C_{cc}(H),

which is zero only if m = 1 or C_{cc}(H)=0.  
Since the graphs are stated to be non-trivial connected graphs, m≠1 and C_{cc}(H) is not generally zero. Hence, the two expressions are not algebraically the same.

The problem asks for TWO closed-form expressions, one for n = 2m – 1 (odd n) and one for n = 2m (even n).

• Candidate 1 supplies both required formulas:
  – For n = 2m – 1: d(n) = 2^m – 1  
  – For n = 2m: d(n) = 3·2^{m-1} – 1

• Candidate 2 supplies only a single expression: 3·2^{m-1} – 1 (implicitly for the even case). It provides nothing for the odd case.

Because the question requires two separate answers and Candidate 2 gives only one, the two candidates are not equivalent (Rule 2).

The two candidates give different closed-form formulas for the perturbed c-Entropy \(\calS(Q)\).

• Candidate 2 expresses \(\calS(Q)\) simply as  
\[
\calS(Q)=\ln\!\left(\frac{\sqrt{Q^{2}+a^{2}}+1}{\sqrt{Q^{2}+a^{2}}-1}\right).
\]

• Candidate 1 gives a much more complicated logarithmic fraction containing the auxiliary quantities  
\(b=Q^{2}+a^{2}-1\) and \(\sqrt{b^{2}+4Q^{2}}\).

Substituting concrete values (e.g. \(a\approx2.164,\;Q=0.5\) or \(a\approx1.313,\;Q=2\)) shows that the numerical results produced by the two expressions differ appreciably (≈0.97 vs 0.93 in the first test, ≈0.89 vs 0.41 in the second), so the formulas are not algebraically equivalent.

Hence the two answers are not the same.

The question requests two specific quantities, \(k_{\text{short}}\) and \(k_{\text{long}}\).

Candidate 1  
• \(k_{\text{short}} = \tfrac{|\,d-2-2p\,|}{2}\)  
• \(k_{\text{long}} = \tfrac12\)

Candidate 2  
• \(k_{\text{short}} = d-2p-2\)  
• \(k_{\text{long}} = 1\)

Comparison:

1. \(k_{\text{long}}\): 1/2 ≠ 1.  
2. \(k_{\text{short}}\): \(|d-2-2p|/2\) is generally not equal to \(d-2p-2\) (different absolute value, different factor of 1/2).

Since at least one of the requested sub-answers differs, the two candidates are not equivalent (Rule 2).

The two proposed formulas are not the same.

Take the simple case n = 3 (odd) and d = 1 (an odd divisor of n):

• Candidate 1  
 d = 1 ⇒ q = 1 only.  
 The inner sum has j = 0 only, giving value 1.  
 With the prefactor 1/d = 1, the whole expression equals 1.

• Candidate 2  
 d = 1 ⇒ k = 1 only.  
 (n/k)!! = 3!! = 3 × 1 = 3.  
 With the prefactor 1/d = 1, the whole expression equals 3.

Since the two formulas already give different numerical values for the same admissible (n,d), they cannot be equivalent.

The question asks for two separate pieces of information:
1. A general formula for F(Dₙ) in terms of τ(n), π(n−1), π(n/2), γ_{n/2}(n).

Candidate 1 supplies
• Formula: F(Dₙ)=τ(n)+π(n−1)−π(n/2)+γ_{n/2}(n)  
• Prime case: F(Dₙ)=π(n)−π(n/2)+1

Candidate 2 supplies
• Formula: F(Dₙ)=γ_{n/2}(n) (only)  
• Prime case: F(Dₙ)=2

The two formulas are clearly different (Candidate 2 omits the τ and π terms), and the prime-case values differ as well (π(n)−π(n/2)+1 vs. 2). Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Candidate 1 provides the count as

 ( p^k / |Aut(G)| ) · ∏_{t=1}^r ∏_{j=1}^{ℓ(t)} ∏_{i=1}^{|L_j^{t}|} φ_i(p^{k-a_t}).

Candidate 2 gives

 ( 1 / |Aut(G)| ) · ∏_{j=1}^r φ_{|L_j^{t}|}(p^{k-a_j}).

Differences:

1. Candidate 1 contains an overall extra factor p^k that candidate 2 lacks.
2. Inside the products, candidate 1 includes, for each linked cell of size m, the product of φ_1, φ_2, …, φ_m, whereas candidate 2 includes only a single factor φ_m. These are generally not equal (the product of φ_1 through φ_m is not equal to φ_m alone).
3. The indexing structure in candidate 2 (mixing j and t) also does not match that of candidate 1.

Because of these substantial algebraic differences, the two expressions cannot be the same count.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two expressions have the same overall prefactor  
  p ᵏ / |Aut(G)|,  
but differ in the product factor:

• Candidate 1 multiplies, for every linked cell L_j^t of size m = |L_j^t|, all terms  
  φ₁(p^{k-a_t}) φ₂(p^{k-a_t}) … φ_m(p^{k-a_t}).

• Candidate 2 multiplies, for every edge e in the spanning tree, only the term  
  φ₁(p^{k-a_e}).

Unless every linked cell has size 1 (so that φ₁ is the only factor needed), the two products are not equal; for a cell of size 2 or more,  
  φ₁² ≠ φ₁ φ₂, etc.

Hence the two candidates generally give different counts, and the formulas are not equivalent.

The only differences are minor spacing and the presence of a box in Candidate 2, which do not change the mathematical content. Hence the two answers are equivalent.

The two candidates give different symbols for the common value:

• Candidate 1: \(M_n\)  
• Candidate 2: \(C_n\)

Nothing in the prompt establishes that \(M_n\) and \(C_n\) denote the same sequence. In typical combinatorial notation \(C_n\) usually refers to Catalan numbers, whereas \(M_n\) often denotes Motzkin numbers (or something else altogether). Since the symbols differ and no equivalence is specified, the answers are not the same.

The question asks for the Conley–Zehnder index as an integer expressed in terms of the signature of S (the difference between the numbers of positive and negative eigenvalues).

Candidate 1: ½ · signature(S)  
Candidate 2: ½ · sign(S)

“signature(S)” is the required integer.  
“sign(S)” is ambiguous and is usually interpreted either as
• the sign of det S (±1), or  
• the matrix sign function, not an integer.

Neither of those equals the signature in general, so the two expressions cannot be assumed to represent the same quantity. Therefore the answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different \(q\)-series.

• Candidate 1  
\[
(-\sqrt{2};q)_\infty \;=\;(1+\sqrt{2})\Bigl(1+\sqrt{2}q+\sqrt{2}q^{2}+O(q^{3})\Bigr)
      \;=\;(1+\sqrt{2})\;+\;(2+\sqrt{2})\,q\;+\;(2+\sqrt{2})\,q^{2}+O(q^{3}).
\]

• Candidate 2  
\[
\frac{(q^{2};q^{2})_\infty+\sqrt{2}(q;q^{2})_\infty}{(q;q)_\infty}
      \;=\;\frac1{(q;q^{2})_\infty}\;+\;\frac{\sqrt{2}}{(q^{2};q^{2})_\infty}
      \;=\;(1+q+q^{2}+O(q^{3}))\;+\;\sqrt{2}(1+q^{2}+O(q^{3}))
\]
\[
      =\;(1+\sqrt{2})\;+\;1\,q\;+\;(1+\sqrt{2})\,q^{2}+O(q^{3}).
\]

The coefficients of \(q\) (and of higher powers) differ:  
Candidate 1 has coefficient \(2+\sqrt{2}\) for \(q\), whereas Candidate 2 has coefficient \(1\).

Hence the two expressions are not equivalent.
The two expressions

1. \((-\sqrt{2};q)_\infty = \displaystyle\prod_{n=0}^{\infty}\bigl(1+\sqrt{2}\,q^{\,n}\bigr)\)

2. \(\dfrac{1}{(\sqrt{2}\,q;q)_\infty}= \displaystyle\frac{1}{\prod_{n=0}^{\infty}(1-\sqrt{2}\,q^{\,n+1})}\)

are clearly different products: every factor in the first product is of the form \(1+\sqrt{2}\,q^{n}\), while every factor in the denominator of the second product is \(1-\sqrt{2}\,q^{n+1}\). There is no standard identity equating these two infinite products, nor does one product equal the reciprocal of the other. Hence the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give entirely different formulas:

Candidate 1:  
Kf(Q'_n(8,4)) = (32 n³ – 2 n)/3 + (36 n² √14 / 7)·( (μⁿ – νⁿ)/((μⁿ + νⁿ) – 2) ).

Candidate 2:  
Kf(Q'_n(8,4)) = n(n² – 1)/(6 μ) + n/ν.

• Candidate 1 contains cubic and quadratic terms in n with a factor √14 and involves μⁿ, νⁿ in both numerator and denominator.  
• Candidate 2 has a simpler rational expression: terms proportional to n³/μ and n/ν with no √14 and no exponentials of n.

There is no algebraic manipulation that can make these two expressions identical for all n, μ, ν. They differ in structure, dependence on variables, and constants.

Therefore, the predictions are not equivalent.

The two answers give the same numerical figure (14 666.67), but:

• Candidate 1 supplies no unit.  
• Candidate 2 explicitly states “IDR 14 666.67 /USD.”

For an exchange-rate question, two orientations are reasonable (IDR per USD or USD per IDR). Because Candidate 1 omits the unit, there is an ambiguity that Rule 1 says makes the answers inequivalent when multiple units could apply.

The exact answer is 
log₂(52! / (26! 26!)) ≈ 48.8490 bits.

Candidate 1 gives 48.8 bits, which corresponds to 48.8000 when written with six significant digits.  
48.8000 and 48.8490 differ at the fourth significant digit, so by Rule 4 the two predictions do not match to six‐digit precision.

Hence the two candidates are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two answers represent numerical values in bits, so compare them.

Candidate 2 gives the exact value  
H = log₂ (52 choose 26).

Compute its numeric magnitude (to check against Candidate 1):

log₂ (52 choose 26) ≈ 48.816 bits  
 (using exact factorial values or Stirling’s approximation).

Candidate 1 states 48.8 bits, i.e. 48.800000 when written to six significant digits.

Comparing to six significant digits (Rule 4):

• Candidate 1: 48.800000  
• Candidate 2: 48.8160…  

They differ starting at the third decimal place, so they are not identical to 6 significant digits.

Hence the two candidates are not equivalent.
The value of  

log₂ (52! / (26!)²) ≈ 48.818 … bits.  

Candidate 1 gives 48.8 (interpreted as 48.800 000 to six significant digits), whereas the exact expression in Candidate 2 evaluates to 48.818 … bits, differing in the 3rd–4th decimal place.  
Since Rule 4 requires agreement to six significant digits for numerical answers, the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give the same numeric value (3.54 × 10⁻⁷).  
However:

• Candidate 1 omits any unit.  
• Candidate 2 explicitly states the unit “C” (coulombs).

According to Rule 1, if one answer lacks a unit and that omission can cause ambiguity, the answers are considered inequivalent. A charge must be specified with a unit (C, μC, etc.); leaving it unit-less introduces ambiguity.

The numeric value of Candidate 1 is 0.66667.  
Expressed to six significant digits, that is 0.666670.

The value of Candidate 2 is 2/3 = 0.666666…  
Rounded (or truncated) to six significant digits, that is 0.666667.

Since 0.666670 ≠ 0.666667 at the sixth significant digit, the two answers are not the same.

The question requires three numerical roots.  
Both candidates supply three numbers in the same order, so we compare each corresponding value.

Convert each to 6-significant-digit form (pad with zeros if fewer digits are given):

1. Candidate 1: 53.52 → 53.5200  
   Candidate 2: 53.5295  
   Comparison: 53.5200 ≠ 53.5295 (mismatch at the 4th decimal place).

2. Candidate 1: 54.25 → 54.2500  
   Candidate 2: 54.2575  
   Comparison: 54.2500 ≠ 54.2575 (mismatch).

3. Candidate 1: 54.76 → 54.7600  
   Candidate 2: 54.7600  
   Comparison: identical.

Because at least one of the three corresponding numbers fails to match to 6 significant digits, the two candidate answers are not equivalent (Rules 2, 3, 4).
The question asks for all the roots.  
Both candidates give three roots, but we must compare each numerical value to six significant digits (Rule 4):

1) 53.52 → 53.5200  
   53.5297 → 53.5297  
   They differ at the 4th–5th significant digit.

2) 54.25 → 54.2500  
   54.2576 → 54.2576  
   They differ at the 4th–5th significant digit.

3) 54.76 → 54.7600  
   54.7615 → 54.7615  
   They differ at the 5th significant digit.

Since at least one discrepancy exists for every root at the required six-digit precision, the two candidate answers are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The question expects two pieces of information:

1. An interval containing the smallest positive root.
2. The root itself, correct to two decimal places.

Candidate 1 supplies only a numerical root “1.8” and omits the interval.  
Candidate 2 supplies both the interval “(1, 2)” and the root “1.80”.

Because Candidate 1 fails to give one of the required answers, the two candidates are not equivalent (Rule 2).

The two answers are not equivalent.

• Candidate 1 specifies “50.7 atm,” explicitly giving the pressure and its unit.
• Candidate 2 gives only “50.7” without any unit.  
  For a pressure prediction, several units (atm, Pa, bar, etc.) are possible; omitting the unit makes the value ambiguous.

According to Rule 1, if one answer includes the unit and the other omits it in a context where multiple units are plausible, the answers are considered inequivalent.

Candidate 1: “7 mol⁻¹”  
Candidate 2: “7.23 kJ mol⁻¹”

1. Units  
   – Candidate 1 gives “mol⁻¹” with no energy unit (J, kJ, etc.), so the dimensionality is unclear.  
   – Candidate 2 gives “kJ mol⁻¹”.

   Even if one assumed Candidate 1 implicitly meant “kJ mol⁻¹”, the values 7.00000 and 7.23000 differ beyond 6 significant digits, so they would still not match (Rule 4).

Hence the two predictions are not equivalent.

The two candidates give pressures in different units, but after converting Candidate 1’s value to the same unit as Candidate 2 (kPa):

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two answers give the pressure in different units:

• Candidate 1: 0.042 atm  
• Candidate 2: 4.27 kPa

Converting Candidate 1 to kPa:  
0.042 atm × 101.325 kPa/atm = 4.25565 kPa.

Now compare (expressed to six significant digits, Rule 4):
• 4.25565 kPa  
• 4.27000 kPa  

They differ at the third significant digit (5 vs 7), so they are not the same to six significant digits.  
Hence, the two predictions are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

The two candidates are both numerical expressions for the same single quantity (the geodesic length).  

• Candidate 1 gives the decimal 2.534324263.  
• Candidate 2 gives the exact expression 2√2 sin(π√2 / 4).  
  Evaluating this expression:
  π√2 ≈ 4.442882938158366  
  (π√2)/4 ≈ 1.110720734539591  
  sin(1.110720734539591) ≈ 0.896019…  
  2√2 × 0.896019… ≈ 2.53432444…

Hence Candidate 2 ≈ 2.53432444, which matches Candidate 1 = 2.534324263 to at least six significant digits (both are 2.53432 …).  
No unit issues or multiple-answer issues arise.

Therefore the two predictions are equivalent.

The question effectively asks for two pieces of information:
1.  The required diameter (or radius) of the telescope’s aperture.
2.  The required focal-length ratio (beam-expander ratio) of the short-focus lens relative to the telescope.

Candidate 1 supplies explicit numerical values for both:
•  Radius ≈ 0.6 m (⇒ diameter ≈ 1.2 m)  
•  F/f ≥ 100  

Candidate 2 gives only:
•  A formula for the diameter, D = 2λ/10⁻⁶ (leaving λ unspecified)  
•  A qualitative statement that F/f must be whatever value is needed to expand the beam to that diameter (no number supplied)

Hence:
•  The aperture statements are not strictly identical: C2 leaves λ unspecified while C1 fixes a number (0.6 m radius) that corresponds only if one assumes λ≈0.6 µm.  
•  The focal-length-ratio statements differ: C1 gives ≥ 100; C2 gives no numeric requirement.

Because at least one required sub-answer (the focal-length ratio) is specified numerically in C1 but not in C2, the two responses are not equivalent (Rule 2 and Rule 8).

The two candidates give complete sets of Fresnel‐coefficients plus Brewster’s angle, so every sub-result must coincide.

• For s-polarization both give
  – Candidate 1:  r_s = sin(θ₂−θ₁)/sin(θ₂+θ₁)
  – Candidate 2:  r_s = (n₁cosθ₁ − n₂cosθ₂)/(n₁cosθ₁ + n₂cosθ₂)

These are algebraically the same (Snell’s law converts one into the other).

• For p-polarization they differ:
  – Candidate 1:  r_p = tan(θ₂−θ₁)/tan(θ₂+θ₁)
  – Candidate 2:  r_p = (n₂cosθ₁ − n₁cosθ₂)/(n₁cosθ₂ + n₂cosθ₁)

Using Snell’s law these two expressions are not equal; numerical checks (e.g. n₁=1, n₂=1.5, θ₁=30°) give opposite signs and very different magnitudes. Hence the two candidates disagree on r_p, and the associated transmission formulae also cannot both be correct.

Because at least one required sub-answer differs, the two sets of answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different quantities.

• Candidate 1: \( \dfrac{27}{128} I_0 \)  (an intensity, explicitly proportional to the incident intensity \(I_0\))  
• Candidate 2: \( \dfrac{27}{128} \)  (a dimensionless number, giving only a fraction)

The question asks for “how much of the intensity … is transmitted.”  An answer can legitimately be expressed either as the transmitted intensity itself (requiring the factor \(I_0\)) or as the fraction of the incident intensity.  Because Candidate 2 omits \(I_0\), it is ambiguous whether it is giving the actual transmitted intensity or merely a ratio.  Under Rule 1, when one answer includes the necessary unit/quantity and the other omits it, causing potential confusion, the two answers are considered inequivalent.

The question has two sub-parts; therefore equivalence must be checked for both.

Sub-part (a):
• Candidate 1 gives  I(θ)=4A² cos²(πa sinθ/λ).  
• Candidate 2 gives  I(θ)=4I₀ cos²(πa sinθ/λ).  

If one identifies A² with I₀, the formulas match, so sub-answers (a) are effectively the same.

Sub-part (b):
• Candidate 1 writes   I(θ) ∼ ρ(a) cos²(πa sinθ/λ).  This simply multiplies cos² by the distribution ρ(a); no averaging over the jitter is performed and no qualitative description of fringe visibility is given.
• Candidate 2 states that, after averaging, the fringe visibility is reduced, yielding a central peak with smeared/washed-out outer fringes.

These two responses are not the same: Candidate 1 provides an expression that is not the averaged intensity pattern described by Candidate 2, and gives no statement about reduced visibility or fringe washing-out.

Because at least one sub-answer differs, the overall answers are not equivalent (Rule 2).

Since the problem merely asks for “the angle θ” and the negative angle is just the symmetric counterpart of the same magnitude, both candidates convey the same essential numerical results; Candidate 1 simply states both possible signs.

Thus the two sets of answers are equivalent.

The two candidates give the same two pieces of information that the problem asks for (field inside the sphere and field outside the sphere) and the mathematical expressions represent the same fields once one notes that

• Candidate 1 treats ε as the absolute permittivity, so ε = εr ε0.  
• Candidate 2 treats ε as the relative dielectric constant εr (dimensionless).

With that identification:

Inside field  
Candidate 1: 3 ε0 /(ε + 2 ε0) E0 = 3 /(εr + 2) E0 = Candidate 2’s result.

Outside field  
The ratio (ε − ε0)/(ε + 2 ε0) becomes (εr − 1)/(εr + 2), matching Candidate 2’s coefficient.  
The vector factor 3(E0·r)r/r^5 − E0/r^3 used by Candidate 1 equals E0 (2 cosθ r̂ + sinθ θ̂)/r^3 used by Candidate 2 for a background field along ẑ.

Hence, after simple unit/notation conversion, both candidates supply identical electric-field expressions inside and outside the dielectric sphere.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give the required “inside” and “outside’’ electric-field formulas, but they use the symbol ε differently.

Candidate 1 treats ε as an absolute permittivity (units of F m⁻¹) and therefore keeps ε₀ explicitly in the ratios:
 E_in = (3 ε₀)/(ε + 2 ε₀) E₀, 
 E_out coefficient = (ε – ε₀)/(ε + 2 ε₀).

Candidate 2 treats ε as the dimensionless dielectric constant (relative permittivity):
 E_in = 3/(ε + 2) E₀, 
 E_out coefficient = (ε – 1)/(ε + 2).

Because the same symbol ε carries different units/meaning in the two answers, the expressions are not the same when ε is interpreted identically in both. This unit/definition mismatch causes ambiguity (Rule 1), so the two candidates’ predictions are not equivalent.
The two candidates use different definitions for the symbol ε.

• Candidate 1 treats ε as an absolute permittivity and keeps ε0 explicitly, giving factors like 3 ε0 / (ε + 2 ε0) and (ε – ε0)/(ε + 2 ε0).

• Candidate 2 omits ε0 entirely and uses factors such as 3 / (ε + 2) and (ε – 1)/(ε + 2), i.e. it treats ε as a dimension-less relative permittivity (with the vacuum value taken to be 1).

Because the same symbol ε carries different units/meaning in the two answers, the numerical factors in the fields are not the same unless one makes an additional identification (ε → ε/ε0) that is nowhere stated. Under Rule 1 this unit/definition mismatch makes the two answers inequivalent.

Both candidates give the same mathematical expression once the common definition β ≡ v/c is used:

Candidate 1: ω₂ = [(1 − β)/(1 + β)] ω  
      = [(1 − v/c)/(1 + v/c)] ω  
      = [(c − v)/(c + v)] ω

Candidate 2: ω₂ = ω [(c − v)/(c + v)]

Since the two expressions are identical (same factor multiplying ω, same units), the answers are equivalent.

The problem requires TWO explicit results: the field inside the sphere and the full spatial expression for the field outside the sphere.

• Inside field  
  Both candidates give the same explicit formula  
  \( \mathbf{E}_{\text{inside}} = \dfrac{3\varepsilon_2}{\varepsilon_1+2\varepsilon_2}\,\mathbf{E}. \)

• Outside field  
  – Candidate 1 supplies the full dipole-perturbed field with the correct coefficient  
    \( \mathbf{E}_{\text{outside}} = \mathbf{E}+ \dfrac{\varepsilon_1-\varepsilon_2}{\varepsilon_1+2\varepsilon_2} a^{3}\!\left[\dfrac{3(\mathbf{E}\!\cdot\!\mathbf{r})\mathbf{r}}{r^{5}}-\dfrac{\mathbf{E}}{r^{3}}\right]\,(r>a). \)

  – Candidate 2 only states qualitatively that the outside field is a “non-uniform field given by the superposition of \( \mathbf{E} \) and a dipole field” without specifying the required coefficient or explicit spatial dependence.

Because Candidate 2 omits the explicit expression demanded by the question, the two answers are not equivalent (Rule 2 and Rule 8: missing required component).

The question asks for three separate results: (a) E(r), (b) V(r), and (c) ΔQ.  
Both candidates give expressions for all three parts, so we compare each part:

1. Electric field E(r):  
   Candidate 1: \(E(r)=\dfrac{V_0}{r\ln(r_2/r_1)}\)  
   Candidate 2: \(E(r)=\dfrac{V_0}{r\ln(r_2/r_1)}\)  
   → identical.

2. Potential V(r):  
   Candidate 1: \(V(r)=V_0\,\dfrac{\ln(r_2/r)}{\ln(r_2/r_1)}\)  
   Candidate 2: \(V(r)=V_0\,\dfrac{\ln(r_2/r)}{\ln(r_2/r_1)}\)  
   → identical.

3. Change in charge ΔQ:  
   Candidate 1: \(\Delta Q = Q\,\dfrac{\ln(r/r_1)}{\ln(r_2/r_1)}\)  
   Candidate 2: \(\Delta Q = Q\)  
   → different unless \(\ln(r/r_1)=\ln(r_2/r_1)\), which is not generally true for arbitrary r. Hence the two answers disagree for part (c).

Because at least one sub-answer differs, the two candidates are not equivalent.

Candidate 1 gives  

F₁ = (Q q r) / (2 π ε₀ R² γ²)  ê_r ,

where q = linear charge density, Q = charge of the single ion, and γ = 1/√(1–v²/c²).

Candidate 2 gives  

F₂ = (q r)/(2 π ε₀ R²) (1 – v²/c²).

Since 1 – v²/c² = 1/γ², F₂ can be rewritten as  

F₂ = (q r)/(2 π ε₀ R² γ²).

Thus F₂ lacks the additional factor Q that appears in F₁.  
Unless Q = 1 by definition (which is not stated), the two expressions are not the same.

Therefore, the two candidates are inequivalent.

Both candidates give a single formula for the force, so Rule 2 is satisfied.  
Compare the two expressions:

Candidate 1  
F = (Q q r)/(2 π ε₀ R² γ²) e_r  
  (with γ² = 1/(1–v²/c²))

Candidate 2  
F = (q r)/(2 π ε₀ R²) (1 – v²/c²)

1. Factor (1 – v²/c²) equals 1/γ², so that part matches.
2. Candidate 1 contains an extra factor Q (the charge of the single ion), giving the force proper (units N).  
   Candidate 2 lacks this factor; its units reduce to N / C (electric-field units), not a force.
3. Candidate 1 also explicitly indicates the radial direction vector e_r, which Candidate 2 omits, but the missing Q already makes the results different.

Because the two formulas differ by the multiplicative factor Q (ion charge), they are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates are not equivalent.

Reason:
• Candidate 1 contains an extra multiplicative factor Q (the charge of the individual ion), giving F ∝ Q q, whereas Candidate 2 gives F ∝ q only.  
• Unless Q were explicitly defined to be 1 (which the question does not state), the two expressions differ by that factor.  
• All other factors (r/(2π ε₀ R²) and (1 – v²/c²)=1/γ²) match, but the missing factor makes the overall results different.

For the same symbol ε these are equal only if ε in Candidate 2 is understood to be the dimensionless relative permittivity ε/ε₀, whereas Candidate 1 treats ε as an absolute permittivity (same units as ε₀). Because the question gives only one symbol ε (“dielectric constant ε”) and does not distinguish two different quantities, the candidates use the same symbol to denote quantities of different dimensions. Hence their formulas yield different numerical results in general.

Therefore the two answers are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two expressions are

Candidate 1: π + arctan(2 / ρ)

Candidate 2: 3π/2 – arctan(ρ / 2)

For ρ > 0 (which is the usual case in a conductor where ρ represents a positive absorption parameter), one has the identity

arctan(x) + arctan(1/x) = π/2 (for x > 0).

With x = ρ/2, we get

arctan(ρ/2) = π/2 – arctan(2/ρ).

Substituting this into Candidate 2 gives

3π/2 – [π/2 – arctan(2/ρ)] = π + arctan(2/ρ),

which is exactly Candidate 1. Thus the two candidates predict the same phase shift (they differ at most by integer multiples of 2π when ρ takes other signs, which does not change the physical phase).

Therefore the answers are equivalent.

Therefore both candidates are choosing the identical multiple-choice option.

Both expressions can be rewritten in the same factored form:

Candidate 1  
ν = (Δ c² / h) (1 + Δ / (2 M))

Candidate 2  
ν = Δ c² (2 M + Δ) / (2 M h)
  = (Δ c² / h) [(2 M + Δ) / (2 M)]
  = (Δ c² / h) [1 + Δ / (2 M)]

Since (2 M + Δ)/(2 M) = 1 + Δ/(2 M), the two candidates give exactly the same formula (with identical units).

The two candidates both write the number 1 × 10⁻⁹, but they are describing different kinds of quantities.

• Candidate 1: “ΔV ≈ 1 × 10⁻⁹.”  Because ΔV is an electric-potential difference, the natural reading is an absolute error expressed in volts (or in whatever unit of potential is being used).  A unit is required but not given, so the answer is ambiguous.

• Candidate 2: “accuracy is approximately 1 × 10⁻⁹, or 0.0000001 % error.”  Here the candidate explicitly states a fractional/percentage error; this quantity is dimensionless.

Thus Candidate 1 gives an (ambiguous) absolute error in potential, while Candidate 2 gives a relative (dimensionless) error.  Since the physical kinds of quantities differ and Candidate 1’s omission of units leaves room for multiple interpretations, the two answers are not guaranteed to represent the same thing.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give the energy levels as a constant factor raised to the power 1/(β+1).  

Inside the parentheses:

• Candidate 1: h α (β+1) n E₀^β  
• Candidate 2: 2π α (β+1) ħ n E₀^β

Since Planck’s constant satisfies h = 2π ħ, the two bracketed factors are identical:

h α (β+1) n E₀^β = (2π ħ) α (β+1) n E₀^β

Hence the whole expressions are algebraically the same, and the energy spectra predicted by the two candidates are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both formulas give  

Candidate 1: Eₙ = [ h α (β+1) n E₀ᵝ ]^{1/(β+1)}  

Candidate 2: Eₙ = [ 2π α ħ (β+1) n E₀ᵝ ]^{1/(β+1)}  

Because ħ = h/(2π), we have 2π ħ = h. Substituting this into Candidate 2 turns its bracket into h α (β+1) n E₀ᵝ, exactly the same bracket as in Candidate 1. The powers (1/(β+1)) are identical. Thus the two expressions are mathematically identical and therefore equivalent.
The two candidates are not provably the same expression.

• Candidate 1 introduces a new symbol “α₀” that the problem statement never defines.  
• Candidate 2 rewrites the answer entirely in terms of the original physical parameters m, ω, ħ, β, α.

Unless one explicitly identifies α₀ with √(m ω / ħ), Candidate 1’s result remains ambiguous, so the two answers cannot be asserted to be identical.  

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The question defines the parameters m, ω, β, α only.  
Candidate 1 introduces an extra symbol α₀ that is never defined in the problem statement or in its own answer, so its expression is ambiguous—its numerical value cannot be fixed without an additional definition.  
Candidate 2 gives a formula solely in terms of the stated parameters (m, ω, β, α). Because of this missing definition, we cannot assert the two expressions are the same. Therefore the two predictions are not equivalent.

 • candidate 1: ħ²/(2I) + ħ²/(2I₀) ± (Δ ħ²)/(4 I²)

With the evidently intended identifications I₀ = I₃ and Δ = A (the parameters introduced in the question), the two expressions coincide term-by-term. No additional levels are missing or added.

Hence every sub-answer given by candidate 1 matches the corresponding sub-answer of candidate 2; the two sets of predictions are the same.
