The two expressions differ by the factor \(4\pi\varepsilon_{0}\).  
In Gaussian (cgs–esu) units one writes the Coulomb energy with \(e^{2}/r\), whereas in SI one writes \(e^{2}/(4\pi\varepsilon_{0}r)\).  Hence

e\(^{2}_{\text{(cgs)}} = \dfrac{e^{2}_{\text{(SI)}}}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\).

Converting Candidate 1 to SI units therefore gives

\[
\Delta E
= \frac{2\,e^{2}_{\text{(cgs)}} R^{2}}{3 a_{0}^{3}}
= \frac{2\,[e^{2}_{\text{(SI)}}/(4\pi\varepsilon_{0})]\,R^{2}}{3 a_{0}^{3}}
= \frac{e^{2}_{\text{(SI)}} R^{2}}{6\pi\varepsilon_{0} a_{0}^{3}},
\]

which is exactly Candidate 2’s result.

Thus, once unit conventions are taken into account, both candidates give the same physical answer.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The question contains four sub-parts (a)–(d).  
For two candidates to be equivalent, every sub-answer must coincide (Rule 2).

(a) Boundary conditions  
• Candidate 1: continuity of ψ and derivative jump 2Ωψ.  
• Candidate 2: continuity of ψ and derivative jump (2mV₀b/ħ²)ψ.  
They coincide only if Ω = mV₀b/ħ², which is not stated by candidate 1.  
So even part (a) is ambiguous.

(b) Transcendental equation for k₀  
• Candidate 1: cos ka + (Ω/k) sin ka = cos Ka  
• Candidate 2: cos (qa) + (mV₀b/ħ²q) sin (qa) = 1  
Right-hand sides differ: candidate 1 leaves cos Ka, candidate 2 fixes it to 1 (K = 0) as required for the lowest propagating energy. Therefore the two equations are not the same.

Since there is already a clear disagreement in sub-answer (b), the two entire answer sets are not equivalent (Rule 2).

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two expressions differ by the factor  

(4 π ε₀)⁻² = 1 / (16 π² ε₀²).

Candidate 2 has the extra denominator 16 π² ε₀² compared with Candidate 1.  
This reflects a change of unit system (Gaussian vs. SI).  
Because the problem statement does not specify which system to use, the omission or inclusion of the (4 π ε₀) factor introduces an unavoidable ambiguity in the numerical value and the units of the answer.

Hence, under the comparison rules, the two candidates are not considered equivalent.
Both answers give the same functional dependence  
 (dσ/dΩ)|θ=0 ∝ (m e A/ℏ²)²  

Candidate 1 is written in Gaussian (cgs) electrostatic units, where the Coulomb constant is 1, so no explicit ε₀ or π appears:

 C1 = A² m² e² / (9 ℏ⁴)

To translate this to SI units, each power of the charge-interaction brings in the factor 1/(4π ε₀).  Since the cross section involves the potential squared, we multiply C1 by (1/(4π ε₀))² = 1/(16 π² ε₀²):

 C1(SI) = A² m² e² / (9 ℏ⁴) × 1/(16 π² ε₀²)  
     = A² m² e² / (144 π² ε₀² ℏ⁴)

Candidate 2 is already expressed in SI units:

 C2 = (m e A / (12 π ε₀ ℏ²))²  
    = A² m² e² / (144 π² ε₀² ℏ⁴)

Thus C1(SI) = C2.  The two candidates are the same result written in different unit conventions.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both answers give the same symbolic dependence
 m² e² A² / (9 ħ⁴)

The only apparent difference is that Candidate 2 keeps the SI-unit factor ε₀ explicitly,

 m² e² A² / (144 π² ε₀² ħ⁴),

while Candidate 1 is written in Gaussian / natural units where 1/(4π ε₀)=1.  Using the identity
 ε₀ = 1/(4π) (Gaussian units)  ⇒  1/ε₀² = 16 π²,
Candidate 2 becomes

 m² e² A² · 16 π² /(144 π² ħ⁴) = m² e² A² /(9 ħ⁴),

exactly the same as Candidate 1.  Hence, after unit conversion the two expressions are identical.

The question has three sub-parts.  
For equivalence, every sub-answer must match.

(a) Eigenfunctions  
• C1:  ψ(θ)=1/√(2π) e^{ikθ}.  
• C2:  ψₙ(φ)=1/√(2π) e^{inφ}, n=0,±1,…  
Same functional form; C2 just states n∈ℤ explicitly. No contradiction → can be regarded as equivalent.

(b) Ground-state occupancies  
• C1:  “0² 1⁴ 2⁴ 3⁴ 4⁴” ⇒ 2 electrons in n=0, 4 in each of n=±1,±2,±3,±4.  
• C2:  “n=0: 2; n=±1,±2,±3,±4: 4 each.”  
These are identical.

(c) Lowest excitation energy and wavelength  
Energy:  
• C1:  ΔE = 9ħ²/(2mr²).  Numerically this equals 2.143 eV.  
• C2:  2.14 eV.  
6-significant-digit comparison: 2.14300 vs 2.14000 → differ.

Wavelength:  
• C1:  λ = 5800 Å = 580 nm.  
• C2:  579 nm.  
6-significant-digit comparison: 5.80000×10² nm vs 5.79000×10² nm → differ.

Since the answers to part (c) are not the same, the two candidates are not equivalent overall.
Both candidates give equivalent answers for parts (a) and (b), and they give the same excitation energy in part (c) (Candidate 1’s formula equals 2.14 eV, the value stated by Candidate 2).

However, for the wavelength they differ:
• Candidate 1: 5800 Å = 580 nm = 5.80000 × 10⁻⁷ m  
• Candidate 2: 579 nm = 5790 Å = 5.79000 × 10⁻⁷ m  

Using Rule 4, numerical answers must match to 6 significant digits. 5.80000 × 10⁻⁷ m and 5.79000 × 10⁻⁷ m differ at the second significant digit, so they are not identical.

Since at least one sub-answer differs, the two sets of predictions are not equivalent.

The two expressions differ only in the mass symbol:

• Candidate 1: −(27 π² g⁸ m³)/(128 ħ⁶)  
• Candidate 2: −(27 π² g⁸ μ³)/(128 ħ⁶)

The problem statement introduces only one particle, whose mass would conventionally be denoted by “m”.  Candidate 2 instead uses “μ”, a symbol that in standard physics notation normally denotes the reduced mass, which need not equal the particle’s mass.  Because the question provides no definition of “μ”, the substitution m ↔ μ is ambiguous.  According to Rule 1, when such ambiguity arises the answers are to be treated as inequivalent.

Hence the two candidates are not guaranteed to represent the same quantity.

Both candidates express ρ(η) in different but algebraically equivalent forms.

Let k = a⁴.

Candidate 1:
ρ² = [k e^{2η}] / [ (16 – 2k) + 2k e^{2η} ].

Candidate 2:
ρ = a² / √[ 2k + (16 – 2k) e^{-2η}]
⇒ ρ² = k / [ 2k + (16 – 2k) e^{-2η}]
Multiply numerator & denominator by e^{2η}:
ρ² = k e^{2η} / [ 2k e^{2η} + (16 – 2k) ].

Denominators are identical after re-ordering:
(16 – 2k) + 2k e^{2η} = 2k e^{2η} + (16 – 2k).

Thus ρ² (and hence ρ with the positive root) is the same in both candidates, and both satisfy the initial condition.

Therefore the two answers are equivalent.

The two candidates give different mathematical expressions:

Candidate 1:  I = −(2/9) G − (π/6) ln 2  
Candidate 2:  I = −(2/3) G

Subtracting them yields  
[(−2/9) G − (π/6) ln 2] − [−(2/3) G] = (4/9) G − (π/6) ln 2,

which is generally non-zero because (4/9) G ≠ (π/6) ln 2.  
Hence the two answers are not equal.

The two candidates give fundamentally different mathematical expressions for the Fourier transform.

• Candidate 1: \(2\,i\,\dfrac{e^{-i b\sqrt{a^{2}+k^{2}}}}{\sqrt{a^{2}+k^{2}}}\)

• Candidate 2: \(2\pi\,J_{0}\!\bigl(b\sqrt{a^{2}+k^{2}}\bigr)\)

The functions \(e^{-iz}/z\) and \(J_{0}(z)\) are not equal (they even have different asymptotic behaviours and analytic properties). Multiplicative constants (2 i  vs 2 π) also differ. Hence the two answers are not equivalent.

Candidate 1 gives a single explicit constant  
 C₁ = π·(25 choose 4)/2²⁴.

Candidate 2 gives a family of constants that still depend on the free integer n:  
 C₂(n) = π·(2n choose n)/2²ⁿ.

Because n is not specified, C₂ can take infinitely many different values.  
No integer n makes (2n choose n)/2²ⁿ equal to (25 choose 4)/2²⁴ (e.g., (25 choose 4)=12 650, whereas (2n choose n) is ≥70 and ≠12 650 for any integer n yielding the same power 2²ⁿ=2²⁴). Therefore the two expressions are not the same constant, and Candidate 2 does not even supply a definite numerical value.

Hence the two answers are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Candidate 1 gives a single, fully-specified constant:  
 π·C(25, 4) / 2²⁴.

Candidate 2 leaves the result in terms of a free integer parameter n:  
 π·C(2n, n) / 2²ⁿ.

Because Candidate 2’s expression changes with n while Candidate 1’s value is fixed (and there is no n specified that makes the two expressions identically the same), the two answers are not the same quantity. Hence they are not equivalent.

The ratio  
\[
\frac{1+e^{x}}{\,2+e^{x}\,}
\]  
is positive for every real \(x\) (both numerator and denominator are \(>0\)).  
Hence  
\[
\ln\!\left|\frac{1+e^{x}}{2+e^{x}}\right| = \ln\!\left(\frac{1+e^{x}}{2+e^{x}}\right)+C_0,
\]  
where \(C_0\) is at most a different constant of integration.

Therefore the two antiderivatives differ, at most, by an additive constant, meaning they represent the same family of primitives.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give the antiderivative

ln((1+e^x)/(2+e^x)) + C

Candidate 1 includes an absolute-value sign inside the logarithm, but the quantity (1+e^x)/(2+e^x) is always positive because e^x > 0 for all real x. Hence |(1+e^x)/(2+e^x)| = (1+e^x)/(2+e^x), so the two expressions differ only by an inessential notation choice. Up to the common arbitrary constant C, the antiderivatives are identical.

Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 each give two results (integral value and limit).  

• Limit: both write the same infinite-product ratio, just with or without the Pochhammer notation, so this part matches.  

• Integral:  

 Candidate 1:  
  Iₙ(a)= (π/ sin πs) · [(q^{1-s};q)ₙ / (q;q)ₙ] · [(a;q)ₙ /(a q^{-s};q)ₙ].

 Candidate 2:  
  Iₙ(a)= (π/ sin πs) · (a;q)ₙ / (q^{s};q)ₙ.

The q-dependent prefactor of Candidate 1, (q^{1-s};q)ₙ /(q;q)ₙ, is not equal to 1/(q^{s};q)ₙ (which is what would be required for equivalence with Candidate 2). For n=1, for example, Candidate 1 gives (1−q^{1-s})/(1−q) whereas Candidate 2 needs 1/(1−q^{s}); they are not equal in general.  

Thus the two candidates disagree on the closed-form expression for Iₙ(a), so the answers are not equivalent overall.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two expressions are

Candidate 1: (1/(1-σ)) [(W/γ(I))^{1-σ} – (R/η(I))^{1-σ}]

Candidate 2: (η(I)^σ R^{-1} – γ(I)^σ W^{-1}) / (σ-1)

Note that 1/(σ-1) = -1/(1-σ), so Candidate 2 equals (1/(1-σ)) [γ(I)^σ W^{-1} – η(I)^σ R^{-1}].

Thus the two will coincide only if

(W/γ)^{1-σ} – (R/η)^{1-σ} = γ^σ W^{-1} – η^σ R^{-1}.

Rewrite the left side:

(W/γ)^{1-σ} = W^{1-σ} γ^{σ-1}, (R/η)^{1-σ} = R^{1-σ} η^{σ-1}.

Compare to the right side terms γ^σ W^{-1} and η^σ R^{-1}. In general

W^{1-σ} γ^{σ-1} ≠ γ^σ W^{-1}, and R^{1-σ} η^{σ-1} ≠ η^σ R^{-1}

except for special parameter choices. Therefore the two overall expressions are not algebraically identical for general values of R, W, η(I), γ(I), σ.

Hence the candidates are not equivalent.

Both candidates give the same mathematical value:

• Candidate 1:  (log 2)/2  
• Candidate 2:  (ln 2)/2  

In the context of calculus and centroid problems, “log” without a specified base is conventionally taken to mean the natural logarithm (ln). Hence both expressions equal (ln 2)/2, so the numerical value is identical.

The two expressions are clearly different:

• Coefficient of ζ(5):

Hence the two results cannot be the same.

Both candidates state that the value of the integral equals the n-th derivative of the Gamma function evaluated at a:  

• Candidate 1:  \(I = \dfrac{\partial^{\,n}}{\partial a^{n}}\Gamma(a)\)  
• Candidate 2:  \(\boxed{\Gamma^{(n)}(a)}\)

The notation \(\Gamma^{(n)}(a)\) is standard for the n-th derivative of \(\Gamma\) at a, identical to \(\dfrac{\partial^{\,n}}{\partial a^{n}}\Gamma(a)\).

Hence the two answers are mathematically identical and therefore equivalent.

The two candidates give different closed-form expressions for the same integral.

Candidate 1: I = (a+1)/(2a) · β(1 − a, 1 + 2a) · Hₐ  
Candidate 2: I = β(a + 1, a + 1) · Hₐ

After canceling the common factor Hₐ, the remaining coefficients are

C₁ = (a+1)/(2a) · β(1 − a, 1 + 2a)  
C₂ = β(a + 1, a + 1).

Using the definition β(x,y)=Γ(x)Γ(y)/Γ(x+y), one finds

C₁ = (a+1)/(2a) · Γ(1−a)Γ(1+2a)/Γ(2+a),  
C₂ = Γ(a+1)²/Γ(2a+2).

These two gamma-ratio expressions are not algebraically identical, and a numerical check (e.g., a = ½) gives C₁ = 2 whereas C₂ ≈ 0.3927, confirming the inequivalence.

Hence Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

   → Candidate 2 introduces an additional 1/r in both pieces compared with Candidate 1.

Because these differing powers of r cannot cancel with anything else in the formulas, the two tensors are not the same.

Both expressions are algebraic rearrangements of the same identity.

Starting from Candidate 2:
   widehat{(∂^k_j f)}(ν) = (i ν_j)^k  hat{f}(ν)

Since ν_j ≠ 0, divide by (i ν_j)^k:
   hat{f}(ν) = (1/(i ν_j)^k) widehat{(∂^k_j f)}(ν) = (1/(i ν_j))^k widehat{(∂^k_j f)}(ν)

This exactly matches Candidate 1. Hence the two candidates give equivalent answers.

The two candidates give different closed-form expressions for the integral.  
After using the duplication and reflection formulas for the trigamma function, Candidate 1 can be rewritten as  

I₁ = (1/√3)[ψ₁(1/3)/(2π) − π/3].

Candidate 2 is  

I₂ = (√3/18)[ψ₁(1/3) − ψ₁(2/3)]  
  = (√3/9) ψ₁(1/3) − (2π²√3)/27.

Dividing each by √3 gives  

I₁/√3 = ψ₁(1/3)/(2π) − π/3,  
I₂/√3 = ψ₁(1/3)/9 − 2π²/27,

which are plainly not the same function of ψ₁(1/3) and π.  
Numerical evaluation (using ψ₁(1/3)≈10.0953) yields

I₁ ≈ 0.559·√3 ≈ 0.968,  
I₂ ≈ 0.391·√3 ≈ 0.678,

confirming the inequivalence.

Therefore, Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 are not equivalent.

Candidate 1’s expression contains two parts:

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give a single numerical expression for the same series S (so Rule 2 is satisfied).  
They are both pure numbers (no unit issues, Rule 1).

1.  Express the summand with partial fractions  
   1/[(3n+1)(5n+2)] = 3/(3n+1) – 5/(5n+2).

   Hence  
   S = 3 ∑_{n=1}^∞ 1/(3n+1) – 5 ∑_{n=1}^∞ 1/(5n+2).

   Shifting the index and rewriting each harmonic-type sum with digammas gives  
   S = ψ(2/5) – ψ(1/3) – ½.

   Using the recurrence ψ(z+1)=ψ(z)+1/z:
   ψ(7/5)=ψ(2/5)+5/2 and ψ(4/3)=ψ(1/3)+3.  
   Substituting, one finds
   S = ψ(7/5) – ψ(4/3).

   Therefore Candidate 2’s answer is the correct analytic form.

2.  Evaluate Candidate 1 numerically:

   a) π/(2√3)·[1 – √{3(1 – 2/√5)}] ≈ 0.396744  
   b) ¼[√5 ln((3+√5)/2) – 2 – ln(3125/729)] ≈ –0.325883  
   Sum ≈ 0.070861.

3.  Evaluate Candidate 2 numerically (using standard digamma values):  
   ψ(7/5) – ψ(4/3) ≈ 0.07086.

   The two numerical values agree to six significant digits (Rule 4).

Hence Candidate 1’s complicated elementary-constant expression equals Candidate 2’s digamma difference. The two answers are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

The two candidates give the result in different forms:

Candidate 1: i π ln²2 + Li₃(2)

Candidate 2: Li₃(½) − (7/8) ζ(3)

Known analytic continuations of the trilogarithm give

Li₃(2) = Li₃(½) − (7/8) ζ(3) − (π²/12) ln 2 + (1/6) ln³2 + (i π/2) ln²2.

Hence

Li₃(2) + i π ln²2 = Li₃(½) − (7/8) ζ(3) − (π²/12) ln 2 + (1/6) ln³2 + (3 i π/2) ln²2,

which clearly differs from Candidate 2 by extra real terms (−(π²/12) ln 2 + (1/6) ln³2) and by an imaginary part ((3 i π/2) ln²2).  Therefore the two expressions are not the same.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different mathematical expressions.

• Candidate 1:  i π ln²2  + Li₃(2)

 – Li₃(2) (principal value) is a complex number; for x>1 its imaginary part is
  Im Li₃(x) = −π ln²x / 2.  
  Hence Im [Li₃(2)] = −π ln²2 / 2.  
  Adding the extra term i π ln²2 leaves an overall imaginary part of
   i π ln²2 − i π ln²2 / 2 = + i π ln²2 / 2  ≠ 0.  
  So Candidate 1 is complex.

• Candidate 2:  2 Li₃(½)

 – For 0<½<1, Li₃(½) is computed by its convergent power series and is purely real.  
  Therefore Candidate 2 is purely real (≈ 1.074426).

Since one result is complex (non-zero imaginary part) and the other is real, the two expressions cannot be equal. They are therefore inequivalent.

Candidate 1 gives the result  
 I₁ = −2 π e^(−b c) cos(r c).

Candidate 2 gives  
 I₂ = [e^(−c(b−ir)) E₁(−c(b−ir)) − e^(−c(b+ir)) E₁(−c(b+ir))]/(2 i).

These two expressions are very different functions of b, c, r.  
For instance, if we formally set r→0⁺ (keeping b>0), the integrand approaches 0, so the integral should tend to 0.  
• Candidate 2 indeed tends to 0, because the two terms in the numerator become equal.  
• Candidate 1 tends to −2 π e^(−b c) ≠ 0.

Thus the two answers cannot be equal for general allowed parameters. They are not mathematically equivalent.

Since, in general, \(\Gamma(b)\) is not equal to \(\cos(\pi a)(-1)^{-a}\) for arbitrary independent parameters \(a, b\) (and no such relationship is stated in the problem), the two results are not algebraically identical.

The two expressions differ inside the Heaviside step-function:

• Candidate 1: Θ(|ω| − |Δ|)  
• Candidate 2: Θ(|ω| − Δ)

If Δ can be negative (its sign is not fixed, since only Δ² appears in the dispersion), then Θ(|ω| − |Δ|) and Θ(|ω| − Δ) are not the same—for example, at Δ = −1 the second step function is always 1 whereas the first becomes Θ(|ω| − 1). Because the formulas are not identical in all cases, the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different closed-form expressions:

Candidate 1: Ω = (π / 2 r²) · ln[ 1 + (r/q) tanh(1/p) ]

Candidate 2: Ω = (π / 2 p q r) · ln[ (q + r)² / (q r) ]

To be equivalent they would need to match for all admissible p, q, r.  
Comparing factors:

1. The prefactors differ: 1/r² versus 1/(p q r).  This already introduces distinct dependencies on p, q, r.

2. The logarithm arguments differ fundamentally: one contains tanh(1/p) (dependence on p inside the log), the other contains only q and r (no p).

There is no algebraic identity that can reconcile these forms for arbitrary parameters. Therefore the two answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give very different closed-form expressions for the same integral.

• Candidate 1 contains
  – an explicit e^{-b} term,
  – a series Σ_{m=0}^{∞} involving the upper incomplete gamma Γ(–1–2m, b) (which itself contains factors e^{-b}), and
  – a ₂F₁ with parameters (–m, 3/2; 2; 1 – b²/a²).

• Candidate 2 is simply
  (π/2)·₂F₁(½, ½; 1; a²/b²),
  i.e. no e^{-b}, no incomplete gamma functions, and no series.

There is no general identity that would convert the complicated, b-dependent series with incomplete gamma functions of Candidate 1 into the single hypergeometric term of Candidate 2 for arbitrary positive a < b. Hence the two results cannot be equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give completely different closed–form expressions.

• Candidate 1 expresses I as  
  e^{-b} + ½(b² – a²) ∑_{m=0}^{∞} a^{2m} Γ(−1−2m,b) {}_2F_1(−m, 3/2; 2; 1−b²/a²).

• Candidate 2 gives  
  (π/2) b e^{-b} {}_2F_1(½, ½; 1; a²/b²).

These formulas have different functional dependence on a and b: candidate 1 involves an infinite series of incomplete gamma functions Γ(…, b), whereas candidate 2 contains no incomplete gamma functions at all and has a completely different hypergeometric parameter set. Substituting a simple limiting case (e.g. a→0, b=1) shows the two results evaluate to different numerical values, so they cannot be algebraically identical.

Hence the two answers are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give completely different closed‐form expressions:

Candidate 1:
I = e^{-b} + \frac{1}{2}(b^{2}-a^{2})\sum_{m=0}^{\infty} a^{2m}\,\Gamma(-1-2m,b)\,
        {}_{2}F_{1}\!\left(-m,\frac32;2;1-\frac{b^{2}}{a^{2}}\right).

Candidate 2:
I = \frac{\pi}{2}\, b\;
        {}_{2}F_{1}\!\left(\frac12,\frac12;1;\frac{b^{2}-a^{2}}{b^{2}}\right).

The functional forms, special functions, and overall dependences on a and b are plainly different (series with incomplete gamma vs. single hypergeometric factor; exponential factor e^{-b} present only in Candidate 1, etc.).  There is no evident identity that would make these two expressions coincide, and a quick numerical check (e.g. a = 1, b = 2) shows they give values differing by orders of magnitude.  Therefore the answers are not equivalent.
For each of the three sub-cases, we must compare the two candidates’ individual answers.

(i)  n = m  
 Candidate 1: 1  
 Candidate 2: 1  
 → identical.

(ii) m > n  
 Candidate 1: 0  
 Candidate 2: 0  
 → identical.

(iii) n > m  
 Candidate 1: “the limit does not exist.”  
 Candidate 2: “±∞.”  

“Does not exist” (neither a finite number nor an infinite value) is not the same explicit statement as “±∞” (the limit becomes unbounded, specifically tending to either +∞ or −∞). Because the answers for sub-case (iii) differ, the two sets of answers are not identical.  
By Rule 2, since at least one sub-answer differs, the candidates are not equivalent.

   • Candidate 1: (π/√2)(z/2)^{1/4}  
   • Candidate 2: √(π/2)

   • Candidate 1 has I_{−1/4} − sgn(ξ) I_{1/4}.  
   • Candidate 2 has I_{−1/4} + I_{1/4}.  
   These are the same only if sgn(ξ)=−1 and even then the overall factor mismatch remains; for sgn(ξ)=+1 they differ in sign as well.

Since both the multiplicative factors and, in general, the Bessel‐function combinations differ, the two expressions are not equivalent.

• Therefore the two expressions are not the same.

The two candidates give different closed-form expressions:

1. Candidate 1:   \(I = -\operatorname{Ei}(0)\;-\;{}_1\Psi_0\!\Bigl[(0,c);\;\dfrac{B}{(A-1)^c}\Bigr]\)

2. Candidate 2:   \(I = \ln A\;-\;{}_1\Psi_0\!\Bigl[(0,c)\mid -\dfrac{B}{A^c}\Bigr]\)

Key discrepancies:

• The first constant terms differ:  \(-\operatorname{Ei}(0)\) vs. \(\ln A\).  These are not the same (indeed \(\operatorname{Ei}(0)\) is divergent while \(\ln A\) is finite for \(A>0\)).

• The arguments fed into the generalized Wright function differ both in sign and in the factor accompanying \(B\):  \(B/(A-1)^c\) vs. \(-B/A^c\).

Because the two formulae are not algebraically identical (and do not reduce to each other under any obvious transformation consistent with the question’s parameters), the answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give the same formula on the domain where the density is required, i.e. for \(u\in[0,1]\).

Candidate 1: \(1_{[0,1]}(u)\,\dfrac{f_{X,Y}\bigl(F_X^{*-1}(u),y\bigr)}{f_X\bigl(F_X^{*-1}(u)\bigr)}\)

Candidate 2: \(\dfrac{f_{X,Y}\bigl(F_X^{*-1}(u),y\bigr)}{f_X\bigl(F_X^{*-1}(u)\bigr)}\)

Because the push-forward measure \(\hat\pi\) lives on \([0,1]\times\mathbb R\), the density only needs to be specified for \(u\in[0,1]\). On this set the factor \(1_{[0,1]}(u)\) equals 1, so the two expressions coincide. Any value the density might take outside \([0,1]\) is irrelevant to the question.

Therefore the answers are equivalent.
Both candidates give the density as 
          f_{X,Y}(F_X^{*-1}(u), y) / f_X(F_X^{*-1}(u)).

Candidate 1 multiplies this by the indicator 1_{[0,1]}(u), while Candidate 2 does not.  
Because the question already specifies that the density is with respect to the product Lebesgue measure on [0,1]×ℝ, the function is only relevant on u∈[0,1]; outside this set the density is immaterial. Therefore the extra indicator factor in Candidate 1 is redundant, and the two expressions coincide on the domain of interest.

The two candidates give different analytical expressions.

Candidate 1  
Re Ψ(½ + ℏω / (2π i k_B T)) − ln(ℏω / k_B T)

Candidate 2  
½ Re ψ(½ + ℏω / (4π k_B T)) − ½ ln(ℏω / (4π k_B T))

Main discrepancies:

1. Argument of the digamma:  
   • Candidate 1: ½ − i ℏω/(2π k_B T) (complex)  
   • Candidate 2: ½ + ℏω/(4π k_B T) (real)

2. Overall scaling factors: Candidate 2 has an extra factor ½ in front of both terms.

3. The logarithm’s inside constant differs (k_B T vs 4π k_B T).

No standard identity converts these distinct forms into one another; hence the two results are not the same.

The question expects a binary response indicating whether \(W\) is (Yes/True) or is not (No/False) a subspace.

• Candidate 1: “False”  
• Candidate 2: “No”

According to Rule 2-8, “False” and “No” are treated as equivalent ways of saying the answer is negative.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
According to Rule 2, the question requires two numerical answers in an ordered list, so we compare each corresponding entry.

Entry 1  
• Candidate 1: 0.333 → written to six significant digits: 0.333000  
• Candidate 2: 1/3 = 0.333333… → written to six significant digits: 0.333333  

These values differ starting at the fourth significant digit. Rule 4 states two numerical answers are equivalent only if they agree to six significant digits, so these are not equivalent.

Entry 2  
• Candidate 1: 0.25 → 0.250000  
• Candidate 2: 1/4 = 0.25 → 0.250000  

These match, but equivalence requires every corresponding answer to match; the first entry already fails.

Therefore the two candidate answers are not equivalent.

The question asks for a 2-element list in the specific order [P_r, P_a].

• first element 2.0 (no unit stated)

The two answers give different numerical values.

• Candidate 1:  
20 √5 + 4 √2 arctan(√5 / √2)  
≈ 20 × 2.2360679 + 5.656854 × arctan(1.58114)  
≈ 44.7214 + 5.7 ≈ 50.4

• Candidate 2:  
20 √5 ≈ 44.7214

Since 50.4 and 44.7214 differ well beyond six significant digits, the predictions are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give the same lists except for the monotonicity intervals:

• Candidate 1: increasing (−π/3, π/3); decreasing (−π/2, −π/3) and (π/3, π/2) – all open.

• Candidate 2: increasing [−π/3, π/3]; decreasing [−π/2, −π/3] and [π/3, π/2] – all closed, hence they include the two critical points x = ±π/3, where f ′(x)=0.

Because the sets differ at those end-points, the answers to sub-parts 1 and 2 are not identical. Rule 2 states that every sub-answer must match; a discrepancy in even one sub-answer makes the whole sets of answers inequivalent.

Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give

• Candidate 2: y =  x / 3 − 4

These expressions are identical only when x > 0 (since |x| = x there).  
For x < 0 they differ: Candidate 1 gives y = −x/3 − 4 while Candidate 2 gives y =  x/3 − 4.  
Therefore the two proposed functions are not the same on the whole domain where the differential equation is defined (x ≠ 0).  

Because the question did not specify that x must be positive, the two answers are not mathematically identical, so they are not considered equivalent under the rules.

Both candidates represent the quantity

I₁ = ∫₀^{π/6} cos²(3θ) dθ.

Candidate 1 gives this integral directly.

Candidate 2 gives (½)∫_{−π/6}^{π/6} cos²(3θ) dθ.  
Because cos²(3θ) is an even function,  
∫_{−π/6}^{π/6} cos²(3θ) dθ = 2∫₀^{π/6} cos²(3θ) dθ = 2I₁.  
Multiplying by ½ yields I₁ again.

Thus the two expressions are mathematically identical.

The question asks for two quantities:

• length = 96 ft  
• height ≈ 26.53 ft

• length = 96 ft  
• height = 8√11 ft.

Numerically, 8√11 ft = 26.532998… ft.  
Comparing the heights to six significant digits (Rule 4):

• Candidate 1: 26.5300 (implicit trailing zeros)  
• Candidate 2: 26.5330 (rounded from 26.532998)

Since 26.5300 ≠ 26.5330 at six significant digits, the two height values do not match.  
Because one of the two required sub-answers differs, the overall predictions are not equivalent (Rule 2).

• Candidate 1: 26.530000

Since one of the requested numerical answers (height) does not coincide to the required precision, the two candidate answers are not equivalent.

Both candidates are definite-integral expressions; we just have to see whether the two integrals are algebraically identical.

Let  
I = ∫₀^{π⁄4} sin²θ dθ.

Candidate 1: 9 I.

Candidate 2:
(1/2) ∫₀^{π⁄4} (3 sin θ)² dθ + (1/2) ∫_{π⁄4}^{π⁄2} (3 cos θ)² dθ  
= (9/2) ∫₀^{π⁄4} sin²θ dθ + (9/2) ∫_{π⁄4}^{π⁄2} cos²θ dθ.

Notice  
∫_{π⁄4}^{π⁄2} cos²θ dθ = ∫_{0}^{π⁄4} sin²u du  
(by substitution u = π/2 − θ), which equals I.

Thus Candidate 2 becomes (9/2)(I + I) = 9 I, exactly the same as Candidate 1.

Hence the two candidates are equivalent.

The two answers are not unambiguously the same.

• Candidate 2 explicitly states “0.3 %”.

• Candidate 1 gives just “0.003” with no unit.  
  – If this 0.003 is meant as a pure (dimensionless) fraction, it corresponds to 0.3 %, matching Candidate 2.  
  – But since the question specifically asks for a percentage, it is also possible to read 0.003 as 0.003 %, which would be an order-of-magnitude smaller.

Because the omission of the % symbol in Candidate 1 leaves room for this ambiguity when multiple unit conventions are possible, Rule 1 says the answers should be considered inequivalent.

Both candidates give two roots, as required.

Candidate 1: x = 2 ± √(13/2)

Rewrite √(13/2):

√(13/2) = √(26)/2

So the roots are
x = 2 ± √26 / 2 = (4 ± √26)/2.

Candidate 2 lists exactly these two numbers: (4 + √26)/2 and (4 − √26)/2 (with decimal approximations).

Thus each corresponding root is identical, merely written in different but algebraically equivalent forms, and the order is irrelevant here.

We need to check whether the two numerical answers coincide.

Candidate 1 gives the numerical value  
  -0.5244.

For Candidate 2 we evaluate  
  4 ln 2 – 3 ln 3 – (5 ln 6)/7776.

1. 4 ln 2  = 2.772588722239781  
2. 3 ln 3  = 3.295836866004329  
   ⇒ 4 ln 2 – 3 ln 3 = –0.523248143764548  
3. 5 ln 6 = 8.958797346140275  
   (5 ln 6)/7776 ≈ 0.0011521087  

Therefore  
  4 ln 2 – 3 ln 3 – (5 ln 6)/7776  
  ≈ –0.523248143764548 – 0.0011521087  
  ≈ –0.5244002525.

Rounded (or written) to six significant digits this is  
  -0.524400.

Candidate 1’s number –0.5244 corresponds to –0.524400 when written with six significant digits.  
Since both results match to six significant digits, the two answers are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Candidate 1 gives a numerical value:  
-0.5244 → interpreted as ‑0.524400 (to six significant digits).

Candidate 2 gives an exact expression  
-3 ln 3  – (5 ln 6)/7776  + 2 ln 4.  
Evaluating this numerically:

ln 3 ≈ 1.098612, ln 6 ≈ 1.791759, ln 4 ≈ 1.386294  
-3 ln 3 ≈ ‑3.295836866  
-(5 ln 6)/7776 ≈ ‑0.001152383  
2 ln 4 ≈ 2.772588722  

Sum ≈ ‑0.524400527.

Thus Candidate 2’s value to six significant digits is ‑0.524401, while Candidate 1’s is ‑0.524400.  
The sixth significant digit differs (…400 vs …401). According to Rule 4, the two answers must match exactly to six significant digits; they do not.

Candidate 1 gives the curvature as  

κ₁(t) = 1 / [16 · |sin(t/2)|].

Candidate 2 gives the curvature as  

κ₂(t) = 1 / [16 · sin(t/2)].

Because κ₁ always uses the absolute value, it is non-negative for all t (as curvature should be), whereas κ₂ can be negative whenever sin(t/2) < 0.  
Since the two expressions differ by the presence/absence of the absolute-value operation, they are not algebraically identical and do not yield the same value for many t (e.g., t = 3π where sin(t/2) = –1).  

Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.
The two candidates give different formulas:

• Candidate 1: κ = 1 / [16 |sin(t/2)|] (absolute value)  
• Candidate 2: κ = 1 / [16 sin(t/2)] (no absolute value)

Because the second expression can be negative whenever sin(t/2) < 0, while curvature must be non-negative, the two answers are not mathematically equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both answers are single antiderivatives of the same integrand, so we just need to see whether the two expressions differ by at most an additive constant.

Candidate 1:
I₁(x)=½ sin(x/2) cos³(x/2)+¾ sin(x/2) cos(x/2)+3x/8+C  
Rewrite with double–angle identities (s=sin(x/2), c=cos(x/2)):

• sin(x/2) cos(x/2)= sin x /2  
• sin(x/2) cos³(x/2)= (sin x /2)·c² = (sin x /2)·(1+cos x)/2 = sin x(1+cos x)/4

Hence  
I₁ = [½·sin x(1+cos x)/4] + [¾·sin x /2] + 3x/8 + C  
  = sin x(1+cos x)/8 + 3 sin x/8 + 3x/8 + C  
  = (1/8) sin x(4+cos x) + 3x/8 + C  
  = (1/2) sin x + (1/8) sin x cos x + 3x/8 + C.

Candidate 2:
I₂(x)=3x/8 + ½ sin x + 1/16 sin (2x) + C.

But sin (2x)=2 sin x cos x, so  
1/16 sin (2x)= (1/16)·2 sin x cos x = (1/8) sin x cos x.

Hence  
I₂ = 3x/8 + ½ sin x + (1/8) sin x cos x + C.

Comparing the simplified forms, I₁ and I₂ are identical term-by-term (and therefore differ only by the arbitrary constant C that is already included). Thus the two candidates are equivalent.

The two expressions can be rewritten for comparison.

Candidate 1  
C₁(x) = C − (1/9)(1 + 3/x²)^{3/2}  
   = C − (1/9)(x² + 3)^{3/2}/(x²)^{3/2}  
   = C − (1/9)(x² + 3)^{3/2}/(|x|³).

Candidate 2  
C₂(x) = −(x² + 3)^{3/2}/(9x³) + C.

For x > 0, |x| = x, so C₁(x) = C₂(x) (they differ only by the constant C).

For x < 0, |x| = −x, hence

 C₁(x) = −(x² + 3)^{3/2}/[9(−x)³] = −(x² + 3)^{3/2}/(−9x³)  
    = +(x² + 3)^{3/2}/(9x³),

whereas

 C₂(x) = −(x² + 3)^{3/2}/(9x³).

Thus, on x < 0 the two expressions are opposite in sign and differ by a non-constant amount (not merely by an additive constant). Therefore the candidates are not equivalent as antiderivatives over the full real domain of the integrand.

The two antiderivatives differ only in the last term:

• Candidate 1 uses  − arctan(cot x)  
• Candidate 2 uses  x

Compute the derivative of − arctan(cot x):

d/dx[−arctan(cot x)] = − [ (−csc²x)/(1+cot²x) ] = 1 ,

since 1+cot²x = csc²x.  
Thus d/dx[−arctan(cot x)] = 1 = d/dx[x].

Hence x and − arctan(cot x) differ only by a constant (indeed −arctan(cot x) = x − π/2 on the principal branch), and any constant difference is absorbed into the arbitrary integration constant C.

All other terms are identical in both candidates, so the two expressions represent the same family of antiderivatives.

The two candidates are not fully equivalent.  
Both give the same maximizing point, (x,y) = (12/5, 6/5) = (2.4, 1.2), but Candidate 1 also supplies the maximum utility value (≈ 16.715) whereas Candidate 2 omits this value.  
Because the problem of “maximizing” a function customarily requires reporting both the maximizing point and the attained maximum value, Candidate 2 provides fewer of the required outputs.  
Hence the answers are considered inequivalent.

Both antiderivatives can differ at most by an additive constant.  
Setting  

s = √(x − 3), t = √(x + 3), so that √((x+3)/(x−3)) = t/s and √(x²−9) = st,

one finds that the non-logarithmic parts of the two expressions cancel exactly, while the logarithmic parts satisfy  

(x + st) · (t − s)/(s + t) = 3.

Hence the difference between Candidate 2 and Candidate 1 equals 9 ln 3, a constant independent of x (on any connected domain where the logs are defined).  
Therefore the two expressions represent the same family of antiderivatives.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both expressions represent antiderivatives that differ only by an (x-independent) constant:

• Writing  
 s = √(x+3), t = √(x−3),

 √((x+3)/(x−3)) = s/t, √(x²−9) = st.

• Candidate 1 yields  
 E₁ = (s/t)(x−15) − 9 ln| (t−s)/(t+s) |.

• Candidate 2 yields  
 E₂ = st − 12(s/t) − 9 ln((x−st)/3).

• Combine the algebra:

 (st/t)(x−15) + 12(s/t) = (s/t)(x−3) = st,

 so E₁ − E₂ = 9[ln((x−st)/3) − ln| (t−s)/(t+s) |].

 But  
 (x−st)/3 ÷ |(t−s)/(t+s)| = 1,  
 hence the bracketed logarithm is ln 1 = 0 for all x in the domain.

Therefore E₁ − E₂ is a constant, and the two antiderivatives are equivalent up to an arbitrary constant of integration.

Both candidates express q(x) as a Fourier integral over the positive frequency axis with the same integrand (up to the dummy integration variable name).  
For the cosine term:

• Candidate 1: (α sin α + cos α − 1)/α²  
• Candidate 2: sin ω/ω + ( cos ω − 1 )/ω² = (ω sin ω + cos ω − 1)/ω²  

These are identical after multiplying the first summand of Candidate 2 by ω/ω.

For the sine term:

• Candidate 1: ( sin α − α cos α )/α²  
• Candidate 2: − cos ω/ω + sin ω/ω² = ( sin ω − ω cos ω )/ω²  

Again identical after combining over a common denominator.  
The integration limits (0 → ∞) and the trigonometric factors cos(…x), sin(…x) match as well. The only difference is the dummy variable name α vs. ω, which has no mathematical effect.

Thus the two expressions are the same Fourier integral representation of q(x).

⇒ Not equivalent.

Both expressions can be rewritten for comparison:

Candidate 1  
S₁ = (π/4)·(12√2 + ln(17 + 12√2))  
   = π·3√2 + (π/4)·ln(17 + 12√2)

Candidate 2  
S₂ = π·(3√2 + ln(1 + √2))  
   = π·3√2 + π·ln(1 + √2)

Note that  
(1 + √2)⁴ = (1 + √2)²² = (3 + 2√2)² = 17 + 12√2,  
so ln(17 + 12√2) = ln[(1 + √2)⁴] = 4 ln(1 + √2).

Therefore  
(π/4)·ln(17 + 12√2) = (π/4)·4 ln(1 + √2) = π ln(1 + √2).

Hence S₁ = S₂.

t = tan(x/2)

and contain exactly the same three elementary parts:

1.  − ln (1 + t^{2/3})
2.  +(1/2) ln (1 + t^{4/3} − t^{2/3})
3.  − √3 arctan[(2 t^{2/3} − 1)/√3]

up to an arbitrary additive constant.

Candidate 1 writes the second logarithm as  

 ln|1 + t^{1/3} t − t^{2/3}| = ln|1 + t^{4/3} − t^{2/3}|,  

which is the same expression candidate 2 gives (without the absolute–value bars).  
The absolute value merely changes the result by at most a constant, which is absorbed in the “+ C.”  
All other terms match identically, including signs and coefficients.

Hence the two antiderivatives differ, at most, by an overall constant of integration and are therefore equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give

S(x) = (1/4) ln( (1+x)/(1−x) ) − (1/2) arctan x,

except that Candidate 1 inserts absolute-value bars around the arguments of the logarithm:

(1/4) ln( |1+x| / |1−x| ) − (1/2) arctan x.

For the domain where the power series actually converges (|x|<1), the quantities 1+x and 1−x are positive, so the absolute values do nothing; the two formulas coincide exactly. Thus, within the intended domain of the question the two expressions are mathematically identical, and the answers are equivalent.

The two antiderivatives are

This difference is not a constant, because

Since the two expressions do not differ merely by an additive constant, the antiderivatives (and thus the answers) are not equivalent.

The two candidates are not equivalent.

Candidate 1 allows two independent integers \(n\) and \(k\), so \(x\) and \(y\) can be shifted by independent multiples of \(2\pi\).  
Candidate 2 uses only one integer \(k\); it always adds the same \(2\pi\)-multiple to \(x\) and \(y\) simultaneously.  Hence it does not cover solutions where, for example, \(x\) is increased by \(2\pi\) while \(y\) is left unchanged (a possibility included in Candidate 1).

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The system requires giving ALL ordered pairs (x,y) that satisfy the two trigonometric products.  
Both candidates try to describe the same two 1-parameter families of solutions:

Family A : (x , y) = (π/6 + πk/2 , π/3 + πk/2)  
Family B : (x , y) = (π/3 + πk/2 , π/6 + πk/2) , k ∈ ℤ.

Candidate 2 writes exactly these two families, with a single integer k.

Candidate 1 rewrites the same families with two integers n and k:

• First alternative  
 x = π/3 + π/2(2n+k) = π/3 + πk/2 + πn  
 y = π/6 + π/2(k−2n) = π/6 + πk/2 − πn

• Second alternative  
 x = π/6 + π/2(2n+k) = π/6 + πk/2 + πn  
 y = π/3 + π/2(k−2n) = π/3 + πk/2 − πn

Because adding ±πn to x and y while adding ∓πn to the other variable keeps
sin x sin y and cos x cos y unchanged, these extra ±πn shifts only generate the
same points as Candidate 2 (or points differing by integer multiples of 2π,
which are identical for sine and cosine).  Conversely, every point in
Candidate 2 is obtained from Candidate 1 by taking n = 0.

Thus the two parameterisations describe exactly the same solution set (Candidate 1 merely lists each solution repeatedly by introducing the extra integer n).

Therefore the two answers are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

Both candidates differentiate to the same integrand  
 d/dx (Candidate 1) = 2 cot⁶(14x)  
 d/dx (Candidate 2) = 2 cot⁶(14x),

so each is a valid antiderivative of 2 cot⁶(14x). Their difference,
 (Candidate 2 – Candidate 1) = –2x – (1/7) arctan(cot 14x),
reduces (using arctan(cot θ) = π/2 – θ + kπ) to a piece-wise constant value on every connected interval where the integrand is defined, hence they differ only by an additive constant. Therefore the two answers are mathematically equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give an antiderivative; they are equivalent if their difference is a constant.

Rewrite Candidate 1:

F₁(x)=−(1/7)[(1/5)cot⁵(14x)+cot(14x)−(1/3)cot³(14x)−arctan(cot(14x))]+C  
  =−cot⁵(14x)/35 + cot³(14x)/21 − cot(14x)/7 + (1/7)arctan(cot(14x)) + C.

Candidate 2:

F₂(x)=−cot⁵(14x)/35 + cot³(14x)/21 − cot(14x)/7 − 2x + C.

Difference:

F₁−F₂ = (1/7)arctan(cot(14x)) + 2x + const.

Now note

d/dx[arctan(cot(14x))] = -14  
⇒ arctan(cot(14x)) = π/2 − 14x  (up to an additive multiple of π, i.e. a constant).

Hence
(1/7)arctan(cot(14x)) + 2x = (1/7)(π/2 −14x) + 2x
                           = π/14  (a constant).

Therefore F₁−F₂ equals a constant; their derivatives are identical (2 cot⁶(14x)), so the two antiderivatives are the same up to an additive constant.

Thus Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 are equivalent.
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

Both candidates give the expression

    −x − 2√x − 2 ln( … ),

with the only difference being the argument of the logarithm:

• Candidate 1: ln |√x − 1|  
• Candidate 2: ln (1 − √x)

The series converges for |√x|<1, i.e. for real x in 0 ≤ x < 1.  
On this domain 1 − √x > 0, hence |√x − 1| = 1 − √x and

ln |√x − 1| = ln (1 − √x).

Therefore the two formulas coincide everywhere the real series sum is defined, and the extra absolute-value bars in Candidate 1 introduce no difference.

Hence the two answers are mathematically equivalent for the intended domain of the problem.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
### Reasoning:
The infinite series converges only for |x| < 1, so for real x we have 0 ≤ x < 1.  
In that interval 1 – √x > 0, hence  
 |√x – 1| = 1 – √x.

Therefore  
 ln|√x – 1| = ln(1 – √x).

Both candidates give exactly the same overall expression
  –x – 2√x – 2 ln(1 – √x)  
on the domain where the series is defined.  
Thus the two answers are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give antiderivatives that differ only by an algebraic rearrangement:

Candidate 1:
2·sin³(x/2)/cos(x/2) − (3/2)x + (3/2)sin x
= 2[sin³(x/2)/cos(x/2)]
   − (3/2)x + (3/2)sin x
Note sin³/ cos = sin/cos − sin cos = tan(x/2) − ½ sin x,
so 2[sin³/ cos] = 2tan(x/2) − sin x.

Therefore Candidate 1 simplifies to
2tan(x/2) − (3/2)x + ½ sin x + C,

which is exactly Candidate 2.

Hence the two answers differ at most by an additive constant and are equivalent.
Candidate 1’s answer:
2 sin³(x/2)/cos(x/2) − (3/2)x + (3/2) sin x + C

Rewrite the first term:
sin³(θ)/cos θ = sin θ (1 − cos² θ)/cos θ = tan θ − sin θ cos θ  
⇒ 2 sin³(θ)/cos θ = 2 tan θ − 2 sin θ cos θ = 2 tan θ − sin(2θ)

With θ = x/2, sin(2θ) = sin x, so

2 sin³(x/2)/cos(x/2) = 2 tan(x/2) − sin x.

Substitute back:

Candidate 1 = [2 tan(x/2) − sin x] − (3/2)x + (3/2) sin x  
      = 2 tan(x/2) − (3/2)x + (−sin x + (3/2) sin x)  
      = 2 tan(x/2) − (3/2)x + (1/2) sin x + C.

This is exactly Candidate 2’s expression (apart from the arbitrary constant C). Therefore the two answers differ only by a constant of integration and are mathematically equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

• For sub-answer 1 (domain) Candidate 1 includes 2⁄3 in the domain (interval (-2⁄3, 1)) and omits nothing at x = 1, while Candidate 2 correctly excludes x = ±2⁄3 and gives (-∞, -2⁄3)∪(-2⁄3, 2⁄3)∪(2⁄3, ∞).  
• Because of this difference, their subsequent concavity interval in item 8 also differs.  

Since at least one required answer differs, the two sets of predictions are not equivalent.
The two candidates are NOT equivalent.

• Sub-answer 1 (domain) is different:  
 Candidate 1 gives (−∞, −2⁄3) ∪ (−2⁄3, 1) ∪ (2⁄3, ∞) whereas  
 Candidate 2 gives (−∞, −2⁄3) ∪ (−2⁄3, 2⁄3) ∪ (2⁄3, ∞).

Because at least one required sub-answer differs, the entire sets of answers are inequivalent (Rule 2).

Both candidates give the same algebraic expression:

Candidate 2:  sin(na/2) · sin((n+1)a/2) / sin(a/2)

Since multiplication is commutative, the order of the two sine factors in the numerator does not matter. Hence the two formulas are mathematically identical and therefore equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give an antiderivative of  

∫ 2 tan⁴(–10x) dx = ∫ 2 tan⁴(10x) dx.  

Rewrite Candidate 1:  
(1/5)[(1/3)tan³(10x) + arctan(tan(10x)) – tan(10x)] + C  
  = tan³(10x)/15 – tan(10x)/5 + (1/5) arctan(tan(10x)) + C.

Candidate 2:  
tan³(10x)/15 – tan(10x)/5 + 2x + C.

The two differ by  
Δ = 2x – (1/5) arctan(tan(10x)).  

For x where tan(10x) is continuous, arctan(tan(10x)) = 10x – nπ (n integer).  
Hence Δ = 2x – (1/5)(10x – nπ) = 2x – 2x + nπ/5 = constant on each continuity interval.  

Since antiderivatives may differ by an arbitrary constant, the two expressions represent the same family of antiderivatives of the integrand (the discontinuities come from the integrand itself).

Therefore Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 are equivalent.
The two expressions differ by  

(1/5) arctan(tan 10x) – 2x  
= (1/5)[arctan(tan 10x) – 10x].

On any interval where tan (10x) is continuous (i.e. between its vertical asymptotes),  
arctan(tan θ) = θ + kπ for some fixed integer k on that interval, so the bracket is the constant kπ.  
Hence on every connected part of the domain where the integrand is defined, the two antiderivatives differ only by a (possibly different) constant; their derivatives are identical and equal to the integrand 2 tan⁴(–10x)=2 tan⁴(10x).

Therefore Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 represent the same family of antiderivatives of the given integrand.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates are antiderivatives of the same integrand.  

• Simplifying the integrand:  
 2 tan(−10 x)⁴ = 2 tan(10 x)⁴.

• Candidate 1:  
 F₁(x)=C+(1/15)tan³(10x)+(1/5)arctan(tan(10x))−(1/5)tan(10x).

 F₁′(x)=2 tan⁴(10x).

• Candidate 2:  
 F₂(x)=C+2x−(1/5)tan(10x)+(1/15)tan³(10x).

 F₂′(x)=2 tan⁴(10x).

Thus each differentiates to the required integrand.

Their difference is  
 F₁(x)−F₂(x)=(1/5)arctan(tan(10x))−2x.  
On any interval where tan(10x) is continuous (i.e., between its vertical asymptotes), arctan(tan(10x)) = 10x + constant, so the difference reduces to a constant. Hence the two antiderivatives differ only by an additive (piece-wise) constant, which is acceptable for an indefinite integral.

Therefore the two answers are mathematically equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both answers are antiderivatives of 2 tan⁴(–10 x).

1.  Candidate 1 simplifies to  
   F₁(x)= (1/15)tan³(10x) – (1/5)tan(10x) + (1/5)arctan(tan(10x)) + C.

2.  Candidate 2 is  
   F₂(x)= 2x – (1/5)tan(10x) + (1/15)tan³(10x) + C.

3.  Their difference is  
   F₁(x) – F₂(x) = (1/5)arctan(tan(10x)) – 2x.

   On any interval where tan(10x) is continuous, arctan(tan(10x)) = 10x – kπ (k is a fixed integer on that interval), so  
   F₁ – F₂ = (1/5)(10x – kπ) – 2x = –kπ/5, a constant on that interval.

4.  Hence F₁ and F₂ have identical derivatives (both give 2 tan⁴(10x)) and differ only by an additive constant (possibly different constants on different continuity intervals of the integrand). This is acceptable for indefinite integrals.

Therefore the two candidates are mathematically equivalent antiderivatives of the given integrand.

Both answers give an antiderivative of  
F(x)=√(1+x²)/x.

Let A=√(1+x²).

Candidate 1:  
F₁ = A + ½ ln|(A−1)/(A+1)| + C.

Note  
(A−1)/(A+1)=x²/(A+1)² ⇒ ln|(A−1)/(A+1)| = ln x² − 2 ln(A+1)=2 ln|x| − 2 ln(A+1).

Hence  
F₁ = A + ½[2 ln|x| − 2 ln(A+1)] = A − ln((A+1)/|x|) + C.

Candidate 2:  
F₂ = A − ln((A+1)/x) + C.

For x>0, |x| = x, so F₁ = F₂ + constant.  
Candidate 2 implicitly assumes x>0 (common when the absolute–value bars are dropped). The two expressions therefore differ, at most, by an additive constant and represent the same antiderivative on any connected domain where they are defined.

Thus the two candidates are mathematically equivalent (up to the usual arbitrary integration constant).

Both expressions reduce to the same function:

The two antiderivatives are

Candidate 2: 2x ln(√(2−x)+√(2+x)) − x + 2 arcsin(x/2) + C.

Both expressions differ only by the overall constant of integration (−C vs. +C), which is arbitrary for an indefinite integral. Therefore they represent the same family of antiderivatives.

• Candidate 1: \(x=\pi n\) (standard notation implicitly means \(n\) is an integer).

Re-ordering the factors (π n vs n π) makes no difference, and the only additional detail in Candidate 2 is the explicit statement \(n\in\mathbb{Z}\), which is the usual implicit meaning of the parameter \(n\) in Candidate 1. Thus the answers are equivalent.
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates express the solution set as all integer multiples of π:

• Candidate 1:  x = π·n  
• Candidate 2:  x = nπ, n ∈ ℤ

These denote exactly the same set {…, −2π, −π, 0, π, 2π, …}. Hence the answers are equivalent.

The two candidates are not clearly giving the same value:

• Candidate 1 states “maximum percentage error is: 0.1” (no percent sign).  
   Since it is labelled as a “percentage,” the most literal reading is 0.1 % (i.e., 0.001 as a fraction).

• Candidate 2 explicitly gives 10 %.

Because the missing unit in Candidate 1 creates ambiguity (0.1 could mean 0.1 % or 10 %), and the explicit value in Candidate 2 is 10 %, the answers cannot be considered unequivocally the same. Under Rule 1, such ambiguity makes them inequivalent.

The two antiderivatives differ in the logarithm’s denominator:

• Candidate 1: ln ((1 + √(1 − x²)) / |x|)  
• Candidate 2: ln ((1 + √(1 − x²)) / x)

When x > 0, |x| = x, so the two expressions coincide up to an additive constant.  
For x < 0, however, ln((1+√(1−x²))/x) is not real-valued, whereas ln((1+√(1−x²))/|x|) remains well-defined (still real). Thus Candidate 2 is valid only on x > 0, while Candidate 1 works on both sides (x ≠ 0 within (−1,1)).

Because their domains (and therefore the antiderivatives) are not the same, the two answers are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two antiderivatives differ by the presence of an absolute value around x inside the logarithm.

Candidate 1: ln((1 + √(1 − x²))/|x|) + C  
Candidate 2: ln((1 + √(1 − x²))/x) + C

• When x > 0, |x| = x, so the two expressions coincide.  
• When x < 0, the argument of Candidate 2’s logarithm is negative, so the expression is not real-valued, whereas Candidate 1 remains real. Moreover, on the interval (–1, 0) the difference between the two expressions is ln(sign x) = ln(–1) = iπ, which is not the same constant as on (0, 1). Hence the two candidates are not the same real antiderivative on the whole domain (–1, 1) \ {0}.

Because they do not give identical values (or even both remain real) on all parts of the domain, the two answers are not equivalent.

Both answers are antiderivatives of the same integrand, so they are equivalent if they differ only by a constant.

Candidate 1:  
C₁(x)= (x−2)/(2(8+2(x−2)²)) + (1/8) arctan((x−2)/2) − 1/(2(x²−4x+8)) + C  
Note 8+2(x−2)² = 2(x²−4x+8), hence  
(2(8+2(x−2)²)) = 4(x²−4x+8).  
Therefore  

 (x−2)/(2(8+2(x−2)²)) = (x−2)/(4(x²−4x+8)).  

Combine the two rational terms:  

 (x−2)/(4(x²−4x+8)) − 1/(2(x²−4x+8))  
 = (x−2)/(4(...)) − 2/(4(...))  
 = (x−4)/(4(x²−4x+8)).

Thus  
C₁(x)= (x−4)/(4(x²−4x+8)) + (1/8) arctan((x−2)/2) + C.

Candidate 2 already gives  

C₂(x)= (x−4)/(4(x²−4x+8)) + (1/8) arctan((x−2)/2) + C.

C₁(x) and C₂(x) are identical up to the arbitrary constant of integration, hence they are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

Both candidates give antiderivatives of the same indefinite integral, so any two correct expressions may differ by an additive constant.

1.  Candidate 2:  
   F₂(x)=−1/(20 sin⁸(4x))+1/(15 sin⁶(4x))+C

   dF₂/dx = (8/5) cos³(4x)/sin⁹(4x), which is exactly the integrand (after simplifying cos(−4x), sin(−4x)).

2.  Candidate 1:  
   F₁(x)=C−(2/5)[(1/3)cot⁶(4x)+(1/4)cot⁴(4x)+(1/8)cot⁸(4x)]

   Rewrite the bracket in terms of csc powers:
      (1/3)cot⁶+(1/4)cot⁴+(1/8)cot⁸
      = (1/8)csc⁸ − (1/6)csc⁶ + 1/24.

   Hence  
   F₁(x)=C − [1/20 csc⁸(4x) − 1/15 csc⁶(4x) + 1/60]  
        = (C−1/60) − 1/(20 sin⁸(4x)) + 1/(15 sin⁶(4x)).

   This is exactly F₂(x) plus a constant shift of −1/60, which is irrelevant for an indefinite integral.

Since the two expressions differ only by a constant, they are mathematically equivalent antiderivatives.

Both candidates give an antiderivative expressed in different but algebraically equivalent forms.

Let w = 1 + 9/x².

Candidate 1:  
F₁ = √w [ (2/1215) w² – (1/729) w – (1/1701) w³ ] + C.

Candidate 2 (rewrite):  
F₂ = –(x²+9)^{7/2}/(1701 x⁷)+2(x²+9)^{5/2}/(1215 x⁵)–(x²+9)^{3/2}/(729 x³)+C  
  = √w w [ –(1/1701) w² + (2/1215) w – (1/729) ] + C  
  = √w [ –(1/1701) w³ + (2/1215) w² – (1/729) w ] + C.

The factor inside the brackets of F₂ is identical to that in F₁:

 –(1/1701) w³ + (2/1215) w² – (1/729) w.

Hence F₁ = F₂ + constant, so the two antiderivatives are the same (difference at most by an additive constant).

Therefore the two candidate answers are equivalent.

The expressions are not identical.

• For the x–coordinates, both candidates give  
  sqrt(4/(1+m²)) = 2/√(1+m²).  
 So the x–coordinates match.

• For the y–coordinates:  
 Candidate 1 has √(4 m²/(1+m²)) = 2 |m|/√(1+m²).  
 Candidate 2 has 2 m/√(1+m²).

 Because √(m²) equals |m|, Candidate 1’s y–coordinate is 2 |m|/√(1+m²), whereas Candidate 2’s is 2 m/√(1+m²).  
 For negative m these differ in sign, so Candidate 1’s points do not satisfy y = m x when m < 0.

Hence Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 are equivalent only for m ≥ 0, but not in general. Since the question did not restrict m, the two predictions are not equivalent.

The two antiderivatives can be rewritten in the same variables.

Let s = sin(2x).

Candidate 1 gives  
F₁(x)= ½[(1/3)s³ + s − ½ ln| (1+s)/(s−1) |] + C  
   = 1/6 s³ + ½ s − ¼ ln|1+s| + ¼ ln|1−s| + C.

Candidate 2 gives  
F₂(x)= 1/6 s³ + ½ s − ½ ln|sec(2x)+tan(2x)| + C.

Since sec θ + tan θ = (1 + sin θ)/cos θ, we have  

ln|sec θ + tan θ| = ln|1 + s| − ln|cos θ|,  
and |cos θ| = √(1 − s²) ⇒ ln|cos θ| = ½[ln|1+s| + ln|1−s|].

Therefore  
−½ ln|sec θ + tan θ|  
= −½[ln|1+s| − ln|cos θ|]  
= −½ ln|1+s| + ½·½[ln|1+s| + ln|1−s|]  
= −¼ ln|1+s| + ¼ ln|1−s|,

which makes

F₂(x)= 1/6 s³ + ½ s − ¼ ln|1+s| + ¼ ln|1−s| + C,

identical to F₁(x) up to an overall constant.

Hence the two candidates provide equivalent antiderivatives.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two antiderivatives differ only in the logarithmic term.

Candidate 2 has  
(1/4) ln| sin x + cos x |.

Candidate 1 rewrites sin x + cos x as cos x (1+tan x) and gives  
(1/4)[ln(1+tan x)+ln|cos x|].

Because sin x + cos x = cos x(1+tan x), we need

 ln| cos x | + ln| 1+tan x | = ln| sin x + cos x |.

Candidate 1 omits the absolute value on (1+tan x).  Hence on intervals where 1+tan x > 0 the two expressions coincide, but on intervals where 1+tan x < 0, Candidate 1’s logarithm is undefined in the real domain, whereas Candidate 2’s expression remains real.  This is not merely a constant difference; it is a domain difference.

Therefore the two answers are not fully equivalent as real antiderivatives of the given integrand.

The two candidates give different multiplicative factors in front of the common fourth–root expression.

Rewrite the desired derivative in logarithmic form:

y = x^{5/4}(5x^2+1)^{1/4}(2+3x)^{-1/12}

⇒ y'/y = ¼[5/x + 10x/(5x^2+1) – 1/(2+3x)].

Thus the correct factor multiplying y is

(1/4)( 5/x + 10x/(5x^2+1) – 1/(2+3x) ),

which is exactly Candidate 2’s prefactor.

Candidate 1’s prefactor is

(50x³ + 35x² + 14x + 10) / (30x⁴ + 20x³ + 12x² + 8x),

which is not algebraically equal to the expression above (e.g. at x = 1 it gives 109/70 ≈ 1.5571, whereas Candidate 2’s gives 1.6167).  

Since the multiplicative factors differ, the two derivatives are not the same.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give an antiderivative of the integrand in the form  

  (6x)^{2/3} − 5(6x)^{1/3} + 5 ln(1 + (6x)^{1/3}) − 6 arctan((6x)^{1/6}) + C ,

just written with slightly different notation:

• Candidate 1 writes (√[6]{6x})⁴ = (6x)^{2/3}, −5 (√[6]{6x})² = −5 (6x)^{1/3}, 5 ln|1 + (√[6]{6x})²| = 5 ln|1 + (6x)^{1/3}|, and −6 arctan(√[6]{6x}).  
• Candidate 2 writes (√[3]{6x})² = (6x)^{2/3}, −5 √[3]{6x} = −5 (6x)^{1/3}, 5 ln(√[3]{6x}+1) = 5 ln(1 + (6x)^{1/3}), and −6 arctan(√[6]{6x}).

The only difference is that Candidate 1 places an absolute-value bar inside the logarithm, which changes the antiderivative only by an (at most piece-wise) constant and thus does not affect its derivative. Hence the two expressions differ at most by an additive constant, which is allowed for indefinite integrals.

Therefore the two answers are mathematically equivalent.
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give the antiderivative as

Both answers describe the same set of x-values.

Candidate 1: union of closed intervals  
  [−π/6 + 2πk, 7π/6 + 2πk] for every integer k.

Candidate 2: real line with the open gaps  
  (7π/6 + 2πk, 11π/6 + 2πk) removed; i.e. keep every point outside those gaps.

For each k, the interval kept by candidate 2 from 11π/6 + 2πk to 7π/6 + 2π(k+1) (endpoints included) is exactly the interval given by candidate 1 with index k+1, while the interval kept by candidate 2 from −π/6 + 2πk to 7π/6 + 2πk coincides with the interval given by candidate 1 with index k. Hence their unions coincide, and the endpoints  −π/6 + 2πk, 7π/6 + 2πk, 11π/6 + 2πk are all included in both descriptions.

Thus the two candidate domains are mathematically identical.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Both candidates describe the same subset of ℝ.

Candidate 1: for each k ∈ ℤ the allowed x satisfy  
 −π/6 + 2πk ≤ x ≤ 7π/6 + 2πk.

Candidate 2: remove from ℝ the open intervals (7π/6 + 2πk, 11π/6 + 2πk).  
The remaining set is the whole real line except where sin x < −1/2; equivalently it is
 [−π/6 + 2πk, 7π/6 + 2πk] ∪ {the single point 11π/6 + 2πk}
which is exactly Candidate 1’s closed interval once one notes that
 11π/6 + 2πk = −π/6 + 2π(k+1),
so those endpoints coincide period-by-period.

Thus the two descriptions define identical domains.

The two candidates describe the same infinite set of zeros.

Mapping candidate 1’s families to candidate 2’s:

1.  −π/2 + 2πn  ≡  3π/2 + 2π(n−1) → candidate 2’s 3π/2 + 2πk  
2.  −2π/3 + 2πn ≡ 4π/3 + 2π(n−1) → candidate 2’s 4π/3 + 2πk  
3.  2π/3 + 2πn          → candidate 2’s 2π/3 + 2πk  
4.  (−1)^n · π/6 + πn gives:  
  • n even ⇒ π/6 + 2πm  → candidate 2’s π/6 + 2πk  
  • n odd  ⇒ 5π/6 + 2πm → candidate 2’s 5π/6 + 2πk  

Thus every solution family in one candidate matches exactly a family in the other, with no extras or omissions. The differing counts (4 vs. 5 listed families) are only due to candidate 1 combining π/6 and 5π/6 into a single formula.

The two expressions match term-by-term except for the logarithm:

• Candidate 1: 3 ln |x+4+√(x²+8x)|
• Candidate 2: 3 ln ( x+4+√(x²+8x) )

Because √(x²+8x) is real for x ≤ –8 or x ≥ 0.  
For x ≤ –8 the quantity (x+4+√(x²+8x)) is negative, so the absolute-value bars in Candidate 1 are essential to keep the result real; Candidate 2 omits them and is undefined (or complex) on that portion of the domain.

Thus the two antiderivatives are not equivalent on the full domain of the integrand.
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give

Candidate 1:   (2x + 1) √(x² + 8x) + 3 ln|x + 4 + √(x² + 8x)| + C  
Candidate 2:   (2x + 1) √(x² + 8x) + 3 ln(x + 4 + √(x² + 8x)) + C

The only difference is the absolute–value bars around the logarithm’s argument.

• For x ≥ 0 the argument x + 4 + √(x² + 8x) is positive, so ln|…| = ln(…) and the two expressions coincide.

• For x ≤ –8 the integrand is still real (the square root is defined), but the argument of the logarithm is negative.  
 – Candidate 1 remains real-valued because ln|…| is defined.  
 – Candidate 2 becomes ln(negative number), which is not defined in the real domain.

Thus Candidate 2 fails to represent a real antiderivative on part of the domain where the integral itself is real, whereas Candidate 1 is valid everywhere the integrand is.

Therefore the two answers are not mathematically equivalent.

Both candidates give antiderivatives that differ only by the constant \( \tfrac{1}{126}\):

• Candidate 1  
 \(F_1(x)=\dfrac{1}{42}\cot^{4}(10x)+\dfrac{1}{63}\cot^{6}(10x)\)  
   = \(\dfrac{1}{63\sin^{6}(10x)}-\dfrac{1}{42\sin^{4}(10x)}+\dfrac{1}{126}\)

• Candidate 2  
 \(F_2(x)=\dfrac{1}{63\sin^{6}(-10x)}-\dfrac{1}{42\sin^{4}(-10x)}\)  
   = \( \dfrac{1}{63\sin^{6}(10x)}-\dfrac{1}{42\sin^{4}(10x)}\)

Thus \(F_1(x)=F_2(x)+\dfrac{1}{126}\).  
Because indefinite integrals are defined up to an arbitrary constant, the two answers are mathematically equivalent.

Both antiderivatives can be rewritten to the same form.

Candidate 1:
1. 1/ sin x = csc x  
2. (3/4)[ln|sin x – 1| – ln|1 + sin x|] = –(3/4) ln| (1+sin x)/(1–sin x) |  
3. sin x / [2( sin²x – 1)] = – sin x /(2 cos²x) = –(1/2) sec x tan x  

Thus candidate 1 becomes  
csc x – (3/4) ln|(1+sin x)/(1–sin x)| – (1/2) sec x tan x + C.

This is exactly Candidate 2.

Therefore the two answers differ only by an (implicit) constant of integration and are equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both answers give an explicit Fourier series, but

1. Argument of the trigonometric terms  
   • Candidate 1 uses cos(n x) and sin(n x) → fundamental period 2π.  
   • Candidate 2 uses cos(n x / 2) and sin(n x / 2) → fundamental period 4π.

   The two sets of basis functions are different; one cannot map term-by-term with the same indexing.

2. Coefficients  
   Even after trying to re-index (e.g. letting n′=2n in Candidate 2 to match cos(n x)), the coefficients do not match: denominators become (n²+4) in Candidate 2 versus (n²+16) (and an extra factor (–1)ⁿ) in Candidate 1.  The sine coefficients also differ by a factor 2.

Because the basis functions and their coefficients do not coincide, the two series are not the same expansion. Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give a single Fourier‐series expression, but the trigonometric arguments are different:

• Candidate 1 uses cos(n x) and sin(n x).  
• Candidate 2 uses cos(n x / 2) and sin(n x / 2).

Since x and x / 2 differ by a factor 2, the two series represent different sets of basis functions (different frequencies). The coefficients are otherwise the same constant factors, but the change in argument cannot be removed by any simple re-indexing; Candidate 2 contains terms that do not appear in Candidate 1 and vice-versa. Therefore the two series are not algebraically identical and do not represent the same Fourier expansion.

Hence the two answers are not equivalent.

The two antiderivatives are not the same up to an additive constant.

The two antiderivative expressions are very different:  

• Both contain the same logarithmic term (with coefficient 2), but  
• Candidate 1 has  –3 · arcsin( … )  
• Candidate 2 has  +6 · arctan( … )

An arcsin of one argument is generally not convertible to an arctan of a completely different argument by adding only a constant; they are genuinely different functions of x. Therefore the two antiderivatives cannot differ merely by an additive constant, so they are not equivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both candidates give explicit antiderivative formulas, but

F₁(x) = 2 ln|x–2+√(x²–4x+2)| – 3 arcsin[ x /((x–1)√2) ] + C  
F₂(x) = 2 ln|x–1+√(x²–4x+2)| + C.

Their difference is  

F₁ – F₂ = 2 ln|x–2+√…| – 2 ln|x–1+√…| – 3 arcsin[ x /((x–1)√2) ] ,

which clearly contains the variable-dependent arcsin term and a non-constant logarithmic ratio, so it cannot reduce to a mere constant. Therefore the two antiderivatives are not the same up to an additive constant, hence the two answers are not equivalent.

Both candidates list two infinite families of zeros, each described modulo π.

1. Family with arctan(1/2):  
   • Candidate 1:  x = arctan(1/2) + π n  
   • Candidate 2:  x = arctan(1/2) + π k  
   These are identical (just a different symbol for the integer).

   • Candidate 1:  x = −π/4 + π n  
   • Candidate 2:  x = 3π/4 + π k  

   Observe that 3π/4 = −π/4 + π.  Shifting the integer index (let k = n − 1) shows the two forms generate exactly the same set of numbers. Hence the two families coincide.

Since each candidate supplies the same two solution sets (just expressed with different but equivalent phase shifts), the overall answer sets are the same.

Both candidates describe the region D in polar coordinates with

 r-range: 0 ≤ r ≤ 4 cos θ

and differ only in the θ-interval they choose:

• Candidate 1: 3π/2 ≤ θ ≤ 5π/2  
 (This is exactly the set of angles where cos θ ≥ 0, written as one continuous interval that wraps past 2π.)

• Candidate 2: 0 ≤ θ ≤ 2π  
 (For θ where cos θ < 0, the upper bound 4 cos θ becomes negative, so no r satisfies 0 ≤ r ≤ 4 cos θ; hence those θ contribute no points, leaving the same geometric region.)

Because polar coordinates are non-unique (adding 2π to θ gives the same point), both descriptions generate exactly the same subset of ℝ², namely the circle x² + y² ≤ 4x.

Thus the two answers are equivalent.
Both candidates give  
• the same radial bound: 0 ≤ r ≤ 4 cos θ  
• angular values that cover exactly those θ for which cos θ ≥ 0.

Candidate 2 lists them as two sub-intervals inside 0-2π:  
 [0, π/2] ∪ [3π/2, 2π].

Candidate 1 uses one continuous interval shifted by 2π:  
 [3π/2, 5π/2] = [3π/2, 2π] ∪ [2π, 5π/2]  
which, modulo 2π, is the same set of directions. Thus both describe the same set of (x,y) points (the same region D), the only difference being redundant θ values in Candidate 1.

Hence the two answers are equivalent.

The question asks for TWO components: the tangential component \(a_t\) and the normal component \(a_N\).

• Candidate 1 supplies both:
  – \(a_t = 0\)
  – \(a_N = \omega^{2}\,|a|\)

• Candidate 2 gives only one expression: “\(a \omega^{2}\)”, with no separate tangential component.

Since Candidate 2 omits a required answer, the two candidates are not equivalent.
The two candidates differ in the expression for the normal component of the acceleration:

• Candidate 1: \(a_N = \omega^{2}\,|a|\)  
• Candidate 2: \(a_N = a\,\omega^{2}\)

Candidate 1 uses an absolute value, ensuring the magnitude is non-negative; Candidate 2 does not. Unless it is explicitly given that \(a\) is always non-negative, the two formulas can yield different values (opposite sign) when \(a<0\). Because the question does not state that \(a\) must be positive, the answers cannot be guaranteed to coincide in all cases.

Therefore, the candidates’ answers are not equivalent.

The two candidates give

Candidate 1:  (1/4) ln(|x+1| / |x−1|) + (1/2) arctan x  
Candidate 2:  (1/4) ln((1+x)/(1−x)) + (1/2) arctan x

For the domain where the series actually converges (|x|<1), both 1+x and 1−x are positive, so |x+1| / |x−1| = (1+x)/(1−x). Therefore the logarithmic parts coincide, and the arctan terms are identical. Hence the two expressions represent the same function on the relevant domain.

Thus the two answers are equivalent.

Both answers give a single formula for d²y/dx².

1.  Put sin t = s, cos t = c.  
   Candidate 2:  −(s² + 2c⁴)/(9216 s⁵ c³).

2.  Candidate 1 numerator  
   (2304 s³ − 1536 s)(c² − s²) − 1536 s²c·(2sc)  
   = −768 s³c² − 1536 s c² − 2304 s⁵ + 1536 s³  
   = 768[−s³c² − 2s c² − 3s⁵ + 2s³]  
   = 768[−s(s² + 2c⁴)]        (after using c² = 1 − s²).

3.  Candidate 1 denominator   
   7 077 888 c³ s⁶ = 27·2¹⁸ c³ s⁶ = 768 · 9216 c³ s⁶  
   = 768 (9216 s⁵ c³).

4.  Hence Candidate 1 value  
   = [768 (−s(s² + 2c⁴))]/[768 s·(9216 s⁵ c³)]  
   = −(s² + 2c⁴)/(9216 s⁵ c³).

This is exactly the expression given by Candidate 2. Therefore the two candidates are mathematically identical.

The question has 5 separate sub-problems, each expecting a numerical value with an associated unit (or an unambiguous implied unit).

Sub-answers comparison:

1. 4 (no unit) vs 4 lbs – likely equivalent (only sensible unit is lbs).
2. 4 (no unit) vs 4 quarts – likely equivalent (only sensible unit is quarts).
3. 4 (no unit) vs 4 pints – likely equivalent (only sensible unit is pints).
4. 6 000 (unit omitted) vs 6 metric tons – ambiguous: 6 000 could be kg, metric tons, etc. Because the question allows both kg or metric-ton answers, omission of the unit introduces ambiguity (Rule 1). Thus the two responses for this sub-problem are not guaranteed to match.
5. 10.25 (unit omitted) vs 10 lb 4 oz – again an ambiguity similar to #4 (10.25 might be pounds, kilograms, etc.).

Since at least one sub-answer (#4, and arguably #5) is ambiguous due to missing units, the two candidate outputs cannot be certified as matching on every required answer (Rule 2 combined with Rule 1). Therefore the overall sets of answers are not equivalent.

Both candidates supply an explicit antiderivative of  

∫ dx /[(x+4)√(x²+2x+5)].

Let  

A = √(x² + 2x + 5) and U = x + 4 + A – √13.  

Candidate 2 gives  

(1/√13) ln| U / (U + 2√13) | + C.          (1)

Candidate 1 gives  

(1/√13) [ ln(√13 – 4 – x – A) − ln(4 + √13 + x + A ) ] + C  
        = (1/√13) ln[ −U / (U + 2√13) ] + C.      (2)

Because −U differs from U only by the factor −1, (2) can be rewritten

(1/√13) ln| U / (U + 2√13) | + (1/√13) ln|−1| + C  
= (1/√13) ln| U / (U + 2√13) | + C′,

where C′ = C + (1/√13) ln|−1| is just another integration constant, independent of x.

Hence the two antiderivatives differ only by an additive constant, so they represent the same family of primitives of the given integrand. The absence of explicit absolute-value bars in Candidate 1 does not change this conclusion, since adding them merely adds a (possible) constant term.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two antiderivatives differ only by an additive constant.

Starting from Candidate 1, combine its two logarithms:

F₁(x)= (1/√13) ln [(√13−4−x−√(x²+2x+5)) / (4+√13+x+√(x²+2x+5))].

Let S = √(x²+2x+5).  Define  

A = √13 − 4 − x − S,  
B = 4 + √13 + x + S,  
D = √13 S − 3x + 1.

One finds algebraically (or by checking two different numerical values of x) that

A/B = −(√13 − 3)·(x+4)/D,

so

F₁(x) = (1/√13)[ln(x+4) − ln D + ln(−(√13−3))]  
      = (1/√13)[ln(x+4) − ln D] + constant.

Candidate 2 is

F₂(x)= (1/√13)[ln|x+4| − ln|D|] + C.

Hence F₁(x) = F₂(x) + (1/√13) ln|−(√13−3)|, i.e. they differ only by an additive constant.  
Since indefinite integrals that differ by a constant are equivalent, the two candidates give the same antiderivative.

Both candidates give antiderivatives that differ only by an additive constant.

Let t = x/3.

Candidate 1 term involving trig functions:
−3 sin³t / cos t  − (9/4) sin 2t.

Candidate 2 term involving trig functions:
−3 tan t  − (3/4) sin 2t.

Compare the −3 coefficients:
tan t − sin³t / cos t = (sin t / cos t) − (sin³ t / cos t) = sin t cos t
= (1/2) sin 2t.

Hence
−3 tan t + 3 sin³t / cos t = −3 (−sin t cos t) = 3 sin t cos t
= (3/2) sin 2t.

So the difference between the two candidates’ entire expressions is

(3/2) sin 2t  − (3/2) sin 2t = 0,

i.e. they differ only by a constant C.

Therefore the two antiderivatives are equivalent.

Both answers give  
½ cot⁴(11x) – cot²(11x) plus a logarithmic term and a constant.

Candidate 1’s logarithmic term:
 ln(1+cot²(11x))

Since 1+cot²θ = csc²θ = 1/sin²θ,  
ln(1+cot²θ) = ln(csc²θ) = ln(1/sin²θ) = –2 ln|sin θ|.

Thus  
ln(1+cot²(11x)) = –2 ln|sin(11x)|,

which is exactly the logarithmic term appearing (with the same sign) in Candidate 2.

All the remaining algebraic terms (½ cot⁴ and – cot²) are identical in both candidates, and any difference can be absorbed into the integration constant C.

Therefore the two antiderivatives differ, at most, by an overall constant and are mathematically identical.

The question asks for two separate results:  
1) the time-dependent spinor ψ(t)  
2) the expectation value ⟨sₓ⟩(t)

Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 both give answers for these two items, but:

• Their spinors are not the same even up to an overall (global) phase:  
 ψ₁(t)=1/√2 (e^{-iωt}, i e^{-iωt})  
 ψ₂(t)=1/√2 (e^{-iωt/2}, i e^{+iωt/2})  
 No single phase factor converts one into the other.

• Their predicted ⟨sₓ⟩ differ:  
 Candidate 1: −(ħ/2) sin(2ωt)  
 Candidate 2: −(ħ/2) sin(ωt)

Since at least one of the required sub-answers is different, the two candidates are not equivalent (Rule 2).

Both sub-problems must be answered.

• Candidate 1 supplies an explicit resonance condition ω = 2 μB_z/ℏ (part a) and a probability formula for part (b).

• Candidate 2 gives only one expression (a probability formula).  It never states the resonance value ω, so part (a) is missing.  (Rule 2: omission of a required answer → inequivalent.)

• Even comparing the probability formulas, the two expressions are algebraically different (different denominators, different oscillation frequency, different overall factor), so they do not match.

Because Candidate 2 lacks the answer to sub-problem (a) and the two probability results disagree, the two candidates are not equivalent.

The two candidates give different mathematical expressions:

• Candidate 1: σₜ = 4 π a² [ tan(k₀ a)/(k₀ a) – 1 ]²  
• Candidate 2: σₜ = π [ a – (ħ tan(k₀ a))/√(2 m V₀) ]²

After inserting k₀ = √(2 m V₀)/ħ and simplifying, Candidate 1 becomes
 σ₁ = (2 π ħ² / m V₀) [ tan(k₀ a) – k₀ a ]²,

whereas Candidate 2 remains
 σ₂ = π [ a – (ħ tan(k₀ a))/k₀ ]².

These differ by both an overall prefactor and the dimensional factors inside the square; they are not algebraically the same, nor dimensionally consistent with each other. Therefore the two answers are inequivalent.

Both candidates give the same mathematical form: a prefactor πħ²/4 divided by (mass × R⁵).  

Candidate 1 writes the mass as μ, while Candidate 2 writes it as m.  
In the context of a single electron (no other body involved), whichever symbol is used represents the electron’s mass, so μ = m here.

Therefore the two expressions are equivalent.

The question has two sub-parts, (a) and (b).  
Both candidates give answers for both sub-parts, so we compare each:

(a) Hyperfine splitting  
• Candidate 1: ΔE = 4 ħ² a  
• Candidate 2: ΔE = 4 a  

These differ by the factor ħ², i.e. they are numerically and dimensionally different unless one redefines a, which neither candidate does. Hence the two answers are not the same.

Because Rule 2 requires every sub-answer to match, the discrepancy in part (a) already makes the overall answers inequivalent. (Even though their part-(b) descriptions are compatible, that cannot compensate for the mismatch in part (a).)

Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.

The question has four sub-parts (a)–(d), so every sub-answer given by the two candidates must match.  

• For (a), (b) and (d) the two expressions are essentially the same if we identify q with e and γ₁₂ with r₁₂; the only difference is an absolute value sign in (a), which doesn’t change the size of the parameter.

 Candidate 1:  ⟨r⟩ = −(2 α q r₁₂²/ħ) sin[ω₀(t − t₁)]  
 Candidate 2:  ⟨−e r⟩ = (2 e² α |γ₁₂|²/ħ) sin(ω₀ t)

They differ in overall sign, contain different charge factors (q vs e²), and one has a phase shift t − t₁ while the other uses t. Because at least one sub-answer is different, the two candidates’ full sets of answers are not identical.

The two candidates give formulas that differ by overall factors of ħ and m.

General-n result  
• Candidate 1: contains ħ and m explicitly.  
• Candidate 2: omits ħ and m entirely.

n = 1 result  
• Candidate 1: E₀ ≤ (ħ/2) √(2λ/m) = ħ √(λ/(2m)).  
• Candidate 2: E₀ ≤ √(λ/2).

Thus Candidate 2’s expressions are those of Candidate 1 only after setting ħ = m = 1, a unit convention that is neither stated in the problem nor in the answer. Because the omission of these physical constants produces an ambiguity in the units (Rule 1), the two answers cannot be considered equivalent.

Both parts of the required answer contain several separate items, so we must compare every item in the two candidate responses.

Sub-problem (a)

1. Lorentz transformation of the position 4-vector:
   • C1 gives the standard boost matrix (x–ct mixing along the x–axis, γ on the diagonal, −βγ off-diagonal).  
   • C2 writes the same transformation in component form (ct′ = γ(ct − βx), x′ = γ(x − βct), y′ = y, z′ = z).  
   These are the same transformation written in two notations; no sign or factor discrepancy appears.

2. Transformation of the momentum 4-vector:
   • C1: (p′_x c, p′_y c, p′_z c, E′) = (γ(p_x c − βE), p_y c, p_z c, γ(E − βp_x c)).  
   • C2: E′/c = γ(E/c − βp_x), p′_x = γ(p_x − βE/c), p′_y = p_y, p′_z = p_z.  
   Multiplying C2’s first two equations by c shows they are identical to C1’s; the y and z components are likewise identical. Hence these transformations coincide.

Sub-problem (b): Relativistic Doppler formulas

Both candidates list all three required cases and give exactly the same expressions:

i) ν = ν₀ √[(1+β)/(1−β)] (approaching)  
ii) ν = ν₀ √[(1−β)/(1+β)] (receding)  
iii) ν = ν₀/√(1−β²) (transverse case)

Notation differences (β vs. β₀) do not change the formula.

All requested components are present in both candidates and are algebraically identical. Therefore, the two candidate answers are equivalent.

(c)  
• Candidate 1 supplies only the final law \(T^{2}/r^{3}=4\pi^{2}/G(m_1+m_2)\) and omits the required scaling transformation.  
• Candidate 2 gives the transformation (coordinates scaled by \(\alpha\) and time by \(\beta=\alpha^{3/2}\)) but states only the proportionality \(T^{2}\propto a^{3}\), leaving out the explicit constant factor.

Thus the two answers are not identical; each is missing information the other includes. According to Rule 2, when required sub-components differ or one is missing, the candidates are not equivalent.
