The question has five sub-parts (a)–(e).  
We must compare each candidate’s explicit answer to every sub-part.

(a)  Both candidates say the motion is planar:  
• C1: “𝒓·𝒉 = 0.”  
• C2: “Conservation of angular momentum implies the motion is confined to a plane.”  
→ Equivalent.

(b)  Position vs. time:  
• C1: x = a sin(ωt+π/2) = a cos ωt, y = (√(m/K) V₀) sin ωt (ω = √(K/m)).  
• C2: x = a cos ωt, y = (V/ω) sin ωt.  
Since V/ω = √(m/K) V, these are the same.  
→ Equivalent.

(c)  Orbit: both eliminate t and obtain an ellipse.  
→ Equivalent.

(d)  Period: both give T = 2π√(m/K).  
→ Equivalent.

(e)  Kepler’s laws:  
• C2 states explicitly: “Only the second law holds; the motion does not fully obey Kepler’s laws.”  
• C1 gives only a formula for T²/a³ that varies with initial conditions, showing the third law fails, but says nothing about the first and second laws. No clear yes/no (or partial-yes) statement is supplied.

Because sub-part (e) is answered differently—C2 gives a definite qualitative verdict, whereas C1 provides an expression without an explicit verdict or mention of the second law—the two sets of answers are not identical and therefore not equivalent (Rule 2: all requested answers must match).

   ω₁ = (√3 + 1)√(g/l),  ω₂ = (√3 − 1)√(g/l).

   • Candidate 1 gives B/A = ∓√3/2 for ω₁ and ω₂.  
   • Candidate 2 gives φ = ∓(2/√3) θ for ω₁ and ω₂.

Since  φ = ∓(2/√3) θ  ⇔  θ/φ = ∓√3/2, Candidate 2’s result is exactly the reciprocal of Candidate 1’s ratio, so the two descriptions are the same up to which coordinate is placed in the numerator. No essential information differs.

Therefore the two answers are equivalent.

2. Part (c):
   • Candidate 1: “n < 3” (strictly less than 3).
   • Candidate 2: “maximum value of n is 3” (which implies n = 3 is still allowed).

Since Candidate 1 excludes the case n = 3 while Candidate 2 includes it, their predictions differ for part (c).

The two candidates give the same expression for the distance of closest approach (a).

For the angular deflection (b):

• Candidate 1: cot θ = (m V₀² b)/k  ⇒ θ = arctan(k/(m V₀² b))  
• Candidate 2: Θ = 2 arctan(k/(m V₀² b))

Thus Candidate 2’s deflection angle is twice Candidate 1’s.

For the differential cross section (c):

• Candidate 1: (dσ/dΩ) = ¼ (k/(m V₀²))² 1/ sin⁴θ  
• Candidate 2: (dσ/dΩ) = ¼ (k/(m V₀²))² 1/ sin⁴(Θ/2)

These two formulas coincide only if θ in Candidate 1 equals Θ/2, but both candidates present their angles as the same quantity requested in part (b). Therefore the answers for parts (b) and (c) are not the same.

Since at least one sub-answer differs, the overall predictions are not equivalent.

The question has three sub-parts, so each candidate must supply three corresponding answers.

Comparison by sub-problem:

(a) Horizontal range  
• Candidate 1: \(R = \dfrac{v_0^2}{g}\sin 2\theta\)  
• Candidate 2: \(R = \dfrac{v_0^2}{g}\sin 2\theta\)  
These are identical.

(b) Drag force expression  
• Candidate 1: \(\mathbf F_{\text{air}} = -\rho A v^{2}\,\mathbf v\)  
• Candidate 2: \(\mathbf F_{\text{air}} = \dfrac12\rho C_d A v^{2}\) (opposite to \(\mathbf v\))  
The two expressions differ by the factor \(\tfrac12 C_d\) (and Candidate 1 omits any drag coefficient). They are therefore not the same.

(c) Motion with Stokes drag & first-order range correction  
The position functions and range corrections given by the two candidates are visibly different (different decay constants and different correction formulas).

Because at least one sub-answer ((b) and (c)) disagrees, Rule 2 dictates the overall answers are not equivalent.

Both candidates give the same numerical factor, 5/4, multiplying the top-quark mass.  
Candidate 1 writes the result with an explicit factor of c² (SI units), while Candidate 2 omits c² (natural units where c = 1).  
Because in particle-physics problems it is conventional to set c = 1, the two expressions represent the same physical energy once unit conventions are accounted for, and no contradictory numerical value is introduced.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>

The two answers differ in their units:

Because the presence or absence of the \(c^{2}\) factor changes the physical dimension and the question does not explicitly state that natural units (\(c=1\)) are being used, the two responses are not unambiguously the same quantity. Under Rule 1 this unit mismatch makes the answers inequivalent.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different formulas:

Candidate 1: Δp = φ² / (4 π r²)  
Candidate 2: Δp = ε₀ φ² / (2 r²)

Even if we try to interpret them as being written in different unit systems (Gaussian vs. SI), the numerical factors and the explicit appearance of ε₀ do not match after any straightforward conversion.  In Gaussian units one would expect Δp = φ² / (8 π r²), not φ² / (4 π r²).  Hence the two expressions are not the same.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two expressions are not algebraically the same.

Let  
• Candidate 1: R₁ = (x/4) [2 + (α₁+α₂) ΔT] / [(α₂−α₁) ΔT]  
• Candidate 2: R₂ = x / [2 (α₂−α₁) ΔT]

Form the ratio:

 R₁ / R₂ = [(x/4)(2 + (α₁+α₂)ΔT)/(α₂−α₁)ΔT] ÷ [x/(2(α₂−α₁)ΔT)]
       = (1/4)(2 + (α₁+α₂)ΔT) × 2
       = ½ [2 + (α₁+α₂)ΔT]
       = 1 + ½(α₁+α₂)ΔT.

Except when ΔT = 0 (or trivially α₁+α₂ = 0), this ratio differs from 1, so R₁ ≠ R₂ for general values.

Hence the two candidates give different predictions.

The question requires answers for two sub-parts:  
(a) the high-temperature value of \(c_v\);  
(b) the exponents \(\alpha\) and \(\gamma\).

Candidate 1:  
(a) \(c_v = Nk\) (i.e. \(N k_B\))  
(b) \(\alpha = 1,\; \gamma = 1\)

Candidate 2:  
(a) \(c_v = k_B\)  
(b) \(\alpha = 1,\; \gamma = 1\)

Comparison:

• Sub-part (a): Candidate 1’s result differs from Candidate 2’s by a factor of \(N\). Since the problem statement involves \(N\gg 1\) particles and does not declare \(c_v\) to be per particle, these two results are not the same quantity; \(k_B\) and \(N k_B\) are inequivalent (Rule 1, Rule 2).

• Sub-part (b): Both candidates give the same exponents, but equivalence for all sub-answers is required; a discrepancy in any part makes the whole set not equivalent (Rule 2).

Therefore the two candidates are not equivalent.

Both candidates supply three sub-answers addressing parts (a), (b) and (c).  
For each part, the content conveyed is essentially the same:

(a) Both state that MB treats particles as distinguishable with no occupancy limit, whereas FD applies to indistinguishable fermions obeying the Pauli exclusion principle.  
(b) Both give qualitative descriptions of the two curves: MB curves broaden/flatten with higher T; FD curves show a sharp drop at low T that smooths out at higher T, and each identifies which curve corresponds to the higher temperature.  
(c) Both explain that MB predicts a specific-heat contribution of 3/2 k_B per electron (far too large), while FD resolves this by allowing only electrons near the Fermi surface to be thermally excited, giving a much smaller heat capacity.

No part required by the question is omitted by either candidate, and no contradictory details appear. Hence the two sets of answers are equivalent.

Both candidates give formulas for

1. the “low-temperature” condition  
2. the average energy E(T)  
3. the molar specific heat C_v(T).

Compare each item:

Low-temperature condition  
• Cand 1: “T_c ≈ 10 ε /(k ln N)” (depends on some unspecified N)  
• Cand 2: “T ≪ 9 ε /k_B”.  
Not the same expression.

Average energy  
• Cand 1: E = ε[ e^{-ε/kT}+10 e^{-10ε/kT} ] / [1+e^{-ε/kT}+e^{-10ε/kT}] (three-level formula).  
• Cand 2: E = ε /(e^{ε/k_BT}+1) (two-level formula).  
The two expressions are different.

Specific heat  
• Cand 1: C_v = R ε² β² [ e^{-βε}+100 e^{-10βε}+81 e^{-11βε} ] /(1+e^{-βε}+e^{-10βε})².  
• Cand 2: C_v = R (ε/k_BT)² e^{ε/k_BT}/(e^{ε/k_BT}+1)².  
Again, not the same formula.

Because the corresponding answers differ for every required sub-problem, the two candidates are not equivalent.
The relevant quantity to compare is the specific-heat expression.

Candidate 1 (exact expression, their “answer 3”):
C_v = R ε² β² [ e^{-βε} + 100 e^{-10 βε} + 81 e^{-11 βε} ] / [1 + e^{-βε} + e^{-10 βε}]².

Candidate 2:
C_v = R (ε/kT)² e^{ε/kT} / [1 + e^{ε/kT}]²
      = R ε² β² e^{-βε}/[1 + e^{-βε}]²   (after rewriting).

The two formulae differ: Candidate 1 contains extra terms involving the third level (10 ε) and large numerical coefficients (100, 81) that are absent in Candidate 2. Thus the two predictions are not algebraically identical except in the extreme low-temperature limit where the extra terms become negligible; the exact answers are different.

Therefore the candidates are not equivalent.

The question has three sub-parts, so answers for (a), (b) and (c) must match exactly.

These are different (U₀ term present vs. absent).

• Candidate 1: S = 2k[N ln N − n ln n − (N−n) ln(N−n)]  
• Candidate 2: S = 2kn[ln(N/n) + 1]  
Not algebraically identical; Candidate 2 is only a leading-order approximation of Candidate 1 for n ≪ N.

• Candidate 1: n = N / (e^{E/2kT} + 1)  
• Candidate 2: n = N e^{−E/2kT}  
Again, Candidate 2 is an approximation of Candidate 1 for large E/(kT), not the same expression.

Since at least one sub-answer differs in each part, the two candidates are not equivalent.

The problem effectively requires three explicit items:  

1. The middle‐plane temperature \(T_m\).  
2. The new net flux for a black middle plane (showing it is half of the original).  
3. The modification of that flux when the middle plane has reflectivity \(r\).

Candidate 1 supplies all three:

• \(T_m=[\tfrac12(T_u^4+T_l^4)]^{1/4}\)  
• \(J_U=\tfrac12\sigma_B\,(T_u^4-T_l^4)\) (half the original)  
• With reflectivity \(r\): \(J_U'=(1-r)\tfrac12\sigma_B\,(T_u^4-T_l^4)\)

Candidate 2 gives only:

• \(T_m=[\tfrac{T_u^4+T_l^4}{2}]^{1/4}\) (same as C1)  
• “The flux density is multiplied by \(1-r\).”

Candidate 2 never states (or even implies) the halved flux for the black middle plane, so one of the required results is missing. Under Rule 2 (multiple sub-answers), omission of a required component means the answers are not equivalent.

The two expressions are algebraically different.

1. Exponential factors  
   • Candidate 1 contains exp(−ε₀/τ) and exp(−ε₀/(2τ)).  
   • Candidate 2 contains exp(+ε₀/(k_BT)) and exp(+ε₀/(2k_BT)).  
   The signs of the exponents are opposite, so the Boltzmann factors are not the same.

2. Pressure constants  
   • Candidate 1 has an extra constant p₀ inside both numerator and denominator.  
   • Candidate 2 has no such term; its denominator is “1 + …” with no additive constant differing from unity.

Because of the opposite exponent signs and the presence/absence of the additional p₀ term, the two formulae cannot be transformed into each other by simple symbol relabelling. They yield different numerical values for the same P, T, ε₀.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two expressions are structurally different.

1. Exponential signs  
   • Candidate 1 contains factors e^{-ε₀/(τ)} and e^{-ε₀/(2τ)} (negative exponent).  
   • Candidate 2 contains factors e^{+ε₀/(k_B T)} and e^{+ε₀/(2 k_B T)} (positive exponent).  
   These cannot both be correct simultaneously for the same ε₀ definition.

2. Overall form  
   • Candidate 1’s denominator is the square of a linear term, [ … ]².  
   • Candidate 2’s denominator is a quadratic polynomial that is not a perfect square.  
   No simple relabelling of symbols (P ↔ p, τ ↔ k_B T, p₀ ↔ 1, etc.) converts one form into the other.

3. Numerical prefactors  
   • Candidate 1 has an explicit factor 2 in the numerator; Candidate 2 does not.

Because of these incompatibilities, the two candidates are not mathematically equivalent answers to the same question.
The two expressions are not algebraically the same.  
• Candidate 2’s numerator is P [exp(ε₀/kT) + exp(ε₀/2kT)], containing two exponential factors corresponding to the two binding energies.  
• Candidate 1’s numerator is p [1 + exp(−ε₀/2τ)]; it lacks a term proportional to exp(±ε₀/τ) and even carries the opposite sign in the exponent of the remaining term.  

The denominators differ analogously (Candidate 1 uses p₀ + …, Candidate 2 uses 1 + …). Because the required exponential factors and signs do not match, no simple rescaling of symbols can make the two formulas identical.

Hence the candidates give inequivalent answers.

Candidate 1 and Candidate 2 give different formulas.

1. Diagonal entries:
   • Candidate 1 explicitly sets (Hα⁻¹)_{ii}=0.  
   • Candidate 2 offers one single formula for every pair (i,j); it would give 0 on the diagonal only if the stated sum happened to vanish automatically, which is not guaranteed by the formula itself.

2. Sign exponent:
   • Candidate 1 uses (|E(P)| – 1)/2.  
   • Candidate 2 uses the “number of non-matching edges in P.”  
     For a general co-augmenting path these two counts are not the same in general, so the signs can differ.

Because the two prescriptions disagree in at least these respects, the answers are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two candidates give different formulas.  
For n = 1, Candidate 1 yields 2^{a₁}, while Candidate 2 gives a₁ + 1; these coincide only for special values (a₁ = 0 or 1) but are unequal in general (e.g., a₁ = 2 gives 4 vs. 3). Hence the expressions are not the same formula for arbitrary aᵢ.

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>

The two expressions are:

Candidate 1: 4(m − 1)(m − 2) / [3 m(2m + 1)]

Candidate 2: (4/3)(m − 1)(m − 2)

Candidate 1 = (4/3)(m − 1)(m − 2) / [m(2m + 1)] = Candidate 2 divided by m(2m + 1).

Since m(2m + 1) ≠ 1 for any positive integer m (and, in fact, for any real m except the impossible simultaneous solutions m = 0 and 2m + 1 = 1/0), the two formulas are different functions of m. Therefore, the candidates are not equivalent.

The two expressions are clearly different.

1. Denominator  
   • Candidate 1: ∏_{k=1}^{∞} (1 − q^{k})^{−2} · ∏_{k=1}^{∞}(1 + q^{k−1/2})  
   • Candidate 2: ∏_{k=1}^{∞} (1 − q^{k})^{−2}

   Candidate 1 contains the extra infinite product ∏_{k=1}^{∞}(1 + q^{k−1/2}), which is absent in Candidate 2.

2. Numerator  
   • For even p, Candidate 1 gives (1 − q^{p}) whereas Candidate 2 also has (1 − q^{p}); but the extra product above still remains, so the two whole expressions differ by that product.  
   • For odd p, Candidate 1’s numerator is (1 − q^{p/2}), not equal to Candidate 2’s (1 − q^{p}).

Because of these mismatches the two characters cannot be the same function of q. Hence the candidates are not equivalent.
Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
The two expressions are structurally very different.

Candidate 1  
char = q^{h_L} · finite factor [(1 – q^{p/2}) times another parity–dependent term] · 
               Π_{k=1}^{∞} (1 + q^{k–1/2}) / (1 – q^{k})²  
     = q^{h_L} · (… ) · [ (–q^{1/2}; q)_{∞} / (q)_{∞}² ]

Candidate 2  
char = q^{h_L} · (q^{p}; q^{p})_{∞} / (q)_{∞}²  
     = q^{h_L} · Π_{n=1}^{∞}(1 – q^{pn}) / (1 – q^{n})²

Thus

• The infinite numerator product in Candidate 1 is (–q^{1/2}; q)_{∞}, containing factors (1 + q^{k–1/2}).  
• The infinite numerator product in Candidate 2 is (q^{p}; q^{p})_{∞}, containing factors (1 – q^{pn}).

These two products are not the same (they involve different signs and exponents: half-integers vs multiples of p).  
Even after including the extra finite factor (1 – q^{p}) or (1 – q^{p/2}) in Candidate 1, there is no identity that converts (–q^{1/2}; q)_{∞} into (q^{p}; q^{p})_{∞}. Consequently the two proposed characters are not algebraically equivalent.

Therefore the candidates give different answers.

The two expressions are not equivalent.

• Take \(m = 2\) and \(n = 1\).

  Candidate 1  
  \(P = 1 - \dfrac{2n(m-1)^{\,n-1} + (m-2)^{\,n}}{m^{\,n}}
      = 1 - \dfrac{2\cdot 1\cdot 1^{0} + 0}{2^{1}}
      = 1 - 1 = 0.\)

  Candidate 2  
  \(P = 1 - \left(1 - \dfrac{1}{m^{2}}\right)^{n}
      = 1 - \left(1 - \dfrac14\right)^1
      = 1 - \dfrac34 = \dfrac14.\)

Since \(0 \neq \tfrac14\), the two formulas give different probabilities. Hence the candidates are inequivalent.

The question requests two separate values:  
1) the time for one oscillation (a period in seconds)  
2) the angular frequency (in units of 10⁷ rad/s).

• Candidate 1 supplies only one number, “4.2”, with no explicit unit or second value.  
• Candidate 2 supplies two numbers: “1.4925 × 10⁻⁷ s” for the period and “4.2097” (presumably × 10⁷ rad/s) for the angular frequency.

Because Candidate 1 fails to give the required period and thus provides fewer answers than the question demands, while Candidate 2 provides both required answers, the two candidates’ outputs are not equivalent (Rule 2).

Candidate 1 gives the numerical value −0.459 (which becomes −0.459000 when written to six significant digits).  
Candidate 2 gives the exact expression cos 1 − 1, whose numerical value is ≈ −0.459697 (= −0.459698 to six significant digits).

Comparing −0.459000 with −0.459698, the values differ beginning at the fourth decimal place; they do not match to six significant digits as required by Rule 4.

Hence the two answers are not equivalent.
The numerical value of cos(1) − 1 (in radians) is approximately −0.459698 (to six significant digits).  
Candidate 1 gives −0.459000, which differs from this at the fourth decimal place, so the two answers do NOT match to six significant digits.

To compare two numerical answers we use Rule 4: treat each as a real number and check whether they match to 6 significant digits.

The two candidates give single numerical answers for the maximum initial velocity.

• Candidate 1: 18.25 (units implicitly m s⁻¹).  
• Candidate 2: √(14 g).  With g = 9.8 m s⁻², this equals √(14 × 9.8) ≈ √137.2 ≈ 11.719 (m s⁻¹).

Comparing the values to six significant digits:

18.25000 ≠ 11.71900.

Since the numerical results are clearly different, the candidates are not equivalent.

Both candidates give the same numerical value: 3.1.  

Candidate 2 explicitly includes the unit “eV,” while Candidate 1 omits the unit.  
The question explicitly asks for the photon energy “in eV,” so it is unambiguous that the number supplied by Candidate 1 must also be in eV. Therefore the omission does not introduce confusion, and the two answers are equivalent.

Final Judgment: Yes <End of Judgment>
The two answers give the same numerical value (3.1) to six significant digits, but:

• Candidate 2 explicitly states the unit “eV,” which the question requires.  
• Candidate 1 gives no unit at all. Because energy could reasonably be expressed either in eV or in joules, omitting the unit introduces ambiguity (Rule 1).

Therefore the two answers are not considered equivalent.  

Final Judgment: No <End of Judgment>
Both answers give the same numerical value for the photon energy:

• Candidate 1: 3.1  
• Candidate 2: 3.10 eV

1. Unit check (Rule 1):  
   – The question explicitly asks for the energy “in eV.”  
   – Candidate 2 includes “eV.”  
   – Candidate 1 omits the unit, but since the question specifies eV, the natural and unambiguous interpretation of the bare number 3.1 is 3.1 eV. No other unit would reasonably apply in this context, so the omission does not create real ambiguity.

2. Numerical comparison (Rule 4):  
   – 3.1 = 3.10000 to six significant digits.  
   – 3.10 eV = 3.10000 eV.  
   The numbers are identical to six significant digits.

Therefore, the two predictions are equivalent.
